<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AsianDiscrimination     07-16 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Asian Discrimination,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rights Commission Puts Off Adoption of Asian Discrimination Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Commission on Civil Rights is
delaying adoption of an extensive report showing that some groups
of Asian Americans tend to earn more than American whites.
   Several commission members said Friday they want the report to
be reviewed by experts on Asian discriminatio. One said the report
could lead to more prejudice against Asian Americans.
   The 289-page report, ``The Economic Status of Americans of Asian
Descent,'' examines census, immigration and other statistics on six
ethnic groups: Chinese, Filipinos, Japanese, Koreans, Asian Indians
and Vietnamese.
   The report by economists on the commission staff says that
native-born U.S. citizens of Japanese and Korean descent earn more
than Caucasians, while those with Chinese heritage earn about the
same and Filipinos and Indians earn less.
   Commission member Mary Frances Berry, expressing concern that
the report might downplay discrimination, said, ``I'm trying to
keep the job from being done on Asian Americans that has already
been done on black men.'' The commission released a report in 1986
that showed that income gaps between black and white men had
decreased dramatically since the 1940s.
   Ms. Berry, one of three black members of the commission, which
includes no Asian Americans, said income is not the only measure of
discrimination and there is a danger that when other Americans see
how well Asian immigrants are doing financially, discrimination
will increase.
   Commissioner Robert A. Destro said the commission does not want
to be in the position of saying to minorities: ``See, everything is
okay. You make a lot of money anyway.''
   Six of the seven commission members voted to postpone adoption
of the report prepared by the commission staff until at least its
September meeting in Los Angeles. The commission is an independent
federal agency, with half its board members appointed by the
president and half by Congress. One seat on the board is vacant.
   The report says there is no evidence the across-the-board
discrimination that existed against Asians in the 1960s exists in
the 1980s.
   ``Adjusting for changing skills and characteristics, the
earnings gap between Asian and non-Hispanic white men decreased
dramatically between 1960 and 1980,'' says an executive summary
included in the report. ``This finding suggests that the economic
progress of Asian men was aided by a decline in anti-Asian labor
market discrimination.''
   The report, however, shows differences between Asian men and
women, between Asian Americans born in the United States and recent
immigrants, and among the six ethnic groups examined.
   It looks at an Asian American population of 3.26 million, making
up about 1.5 percent of the U.S. population.
   It cites evidence that new immigrants from Asia initially earn
less than similar non-Hispanic white immigrants but that they end
up earning more after about 11 years in this country.
   Asian women, both immigrants and native-born, tend to earn more
than white women, the report said. It noted that that more Asian
American women work, partly because the more closely knit family
structure with many relatives often living together allows other
family members to take care of children.
   Poverty rates for U.S.-born Chinese, Japanese and Korean
families are lower than the general population, while poverty rates
for Filipino and Indian families are higher, and Vietnamese
immigrant families have substantially higher levels of poverty,
according to the report.
   James Cunningham, assistant staff director who oversaw the
project, said the data raise several questions requiring further
research, including the possibility of discrimination at higher
levels of employment.
   He said that Asians are over-represented in professional jobs
but under-represented in managerial positions. ``We don't know
whether this is by choice or because of discrimination,''
Cunningham said.
   He said that while Asians are showing overall success in many
areas and discrimination has decreased, prejudices still affect
some Asian groups.
   ``This is by no means to say there is an Asian success story,''
he said.
</TEXT>
