<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DroughtTaskForce     07-16 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought Task Force,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Task Force to Tour 10 Dought-Stricken States Next Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal task force headed by Secretary of
Agriculture Richard Lyng will visit Indiana, Missouri, Tennessee
and Ohio on Tuesday as it kicks off a tour of 10 drought-stricken
states.
   A schedule released Friday by the White House shows stops in
Mansfield, Ohio; Lafayette, Ind.; Jackson, Tenn., and Cape
Girardeau, Mo., on Tuesday.
   On Wednesday, the group is to tour locations around Cedar
Rapids, Iowa, Aberdeen, S.D., and Grand Forks, N.D.
   The inspection trip will wind up Thursday with stops at St.
Cloud, Minn.; Lacrosse, Wis., and Midland, Mich.
   The group will return to Washington on Thursday afternoon.
   President Reagan announced plans for the inspection trip during
his own visit to drought-afflicted farm areas in Southern Illinois
on Thursday,.
   On the return flight to Washington aboard Air Force One,
Secretary of Agriculture Richard Lyng said he believed there were
11 states on the tour, giving rise to erroneous reports that
Oklahoma would be included.
</TEXT>
