<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pop singer Jonathan ``Chico'' DeBarge was
dropped from the Sheriff's Department anti-drug telethon this
weekend after he was arrested for investigation of ferrying 2.2
pounds of cocaine, officials said.
   ``I wouldn't say it's embarrassing. We didn't want to send out
the wrong message,'' telethon organizer Sgt. Richard Shaw said
Friday.
   The telethon begins this afternoon and runs through early Sunday
to raise money for the Substance Abuse Narcotics Education program,
or SANE. The 3-year-old program is designed to help elementary
school students avoid drugs.
   DeBarge, 22, was free on $500,000 bail in Grand Rapids, Mich.,
after his arrest last week for investigation of transporting
cocaine from Los Angeles to Michigan. Although free, DeBarge may
not leave the area without permission, federal authorities said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of Soviet emigre writer
Alexander Solzhenitsyn denied a German radio report that she and
her husband would return to their homeland for a visit and that his
works would be published there.
   The Munich-based Bayerischer Rundfunk radio station said
Solzhenitsyn and his wife planned to visit the Soviet Union in
November or December and that the Soviet Union wanted to publish
all his works, including the novella ``Cancer Ward'' and the
non-fiction ``The Gulag Archipelago,'' an expose of terror and
hopelessness in Soviet labor camps.
   It said the information came from its correspondent in New York
City.
   But Natalya Solzhenitsyn said, ``I never talked to (an) unnamed
reporter from New York.''
   ``Everything is (a) lie. Everything is false,'' Mrs.
Solzhenitsyn said Friday in a telephone interview from her home in
Cavendish, Vt.
   Solzhenitsyn incurred the wrath of the Soviet Union's leadership
with novels such as ``The First Circle.'' In February 1974,
Solzhenitsyn was arrested, formally accused of treason, stripped of
his citizenship and deported to the West.
   He won the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1970.
</TEXT>
