<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe DiMaggio, the Hall of Fame New York
Yankee centerfielder, was in ``excellent'' condition and in high
spirits following successful surgery to repair an abdominal aortic
aneurysm, his doctor said.
   The 74-year-old baseball great also was buoyed by a telegram
from President and Nancy Reagan, his cardiologist Dr. Philip Samet
said Friday. DiMaggio entered the hospital Monday and went into
surgery Thursday.
   ``He's doing great. He's making excellent progress from surgery
and will be moved out of the surgical intensive care unit sometime
over the weekend,'' said Lori Fagenholz, a Mount Sinai Medical
Center spokeswoman.
   ``Joe is getting inundated by flowers, cards and telephone
calls,'' she said.
   DiMaggio, who had a pacemaker implanted in 1987, elected to have
the aneurysm repaired after it suddenly showed signs of growth. An
aneurysm is a weakening of an artery wall that permits it to
balloon out. It can be fatal if it ruptures, Ms. Fagenholz said.
