<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MarineRunner     07-16 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marine Runner,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marine Major With One Lung Ends Death Valley-Mount Whitney Run</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONE PINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Marine Corps major who lost a lung
when he was wounded in Vietnam gave up a grueling run Friday from
the lowest point in North America to the highest mountaintop in the
continental United States.
   Hallucinating, suffering from cramps and dehydration, and
showing a temperature of 101.6 degrees, Maj. John Bates quit the
run on the flank of Mount Whitney that he had begun in Death Valley
on Wednesday night.
   Bates, 42, said he was ``done in'' by a steep 11-mile grade and
temperatures of more than 100 degrees Friday, the Los Angeles Times
reported.
   ``I tried to climb into a bush thinking it was my wife's car,''
he said, managing a weary smile. ``I was also violently
regurgitating anything I ate.''
   Bates left Badwater, Calif., at 282 feet below sea level, at 8
p.m. Wednesday. His goal was to beat the existng record to the
summit of Mount Whitney, at 14,464 feet, some 146 miles away.
   The run's fastest recorded time is 45 hours, 15 minutes, set by
Gil Cornell of Lone Pine in 1987.
   Bates previously ran the course in September 1986, posting his
personal best time of 63 hours, with two eight-hour sleep breaks
during that run.
   ``He picked one of the toughest terrains in the world at a real
bad time of the year,'' said Russell Marsh, acting chief ranger at
Death Valley National Monument.
   ``We are talking about an average temperature of 120 degrees and
a ground-floor temperature of 200 degrees.''
   Bates 36-year-old wife, Stephanie, who was accompanying the
Marine in a camper said she found that her husband's temperature
was 101.6 degrees.
   Over his objections, she said, ``I decided to drive him into
Lone Pine.
   ``He said, `No, just let me rest a little longer.'
   ``I said, `Try to fight me.' I knew he could not.''
   Bates lost a lung when a Viet Cong bullet hit his chest Dec. 17,
1966. During the war, he also caught grenade shrapnel in his left
knee and lost all feeling in two toes after stepping on a trap.
   Bates, who is en route to his next assignment at the Marine
Corps Air Station at Kanehoe, Hawaii, said he was making the run
for personal satisfaction.
   ``It also gives publicity to the Marine Corps and disabled
Vietnam veterans by showing there is a lot more they can do with
their lives,'' he said.
</TEXT>
