<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Anglican-Women     07-16 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Anglican-Women,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World's Anglican Bishops Split Over Women's Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anglican bishops representing 70
million faithful worldwide face bitter divisions over ordination of
women as priests and bishops when they open an international
conference this weekend.
   ``The omens are not good for the 12th Lambeth Conference.
Inevitably it will be dominated by questions about women priests
and women bishops,'' said an editorial in the Church of England
independent weekly, Church Times.
   ``It seems that bishops advocating and bishops resisting the
ordination of women are on a collision course,'' the weekly said.
   The three-week meeting of the Lambeth Conference, held every 10
years, officially opens on Sunday with a service in Canterbury
Cathedral and closes with another there on Sunday, Aug. 7.
   Anglicans are the world's largest group of Christians after the
estimated 700 million Roman Catholics.
   The conference, which will discuss the work of the church,
relations with other Christians and social questions, has been
overshadowed by the controversy over women priests, already
ordained in some of the Anglican Communion's 27 provinces but
rejected in others.
   Even more divisive is the possibility that Anglicans in the U.S.
Episcopal Church will consecrate their first woman bishop this year.
   Bishops in many provinces have said that while they might
tolerate women priests, the prospect of a woman bishop could lead
to severing of ties between their churches and the Anglican
Communion.
   Each province is self-governing, unlike the Catholic Church,
which is ruled centrally by the pope in the Vatican. But the state
Church of England is looked to for guidance, and its spiritual
head, Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, is the world Anglican
leader.
   Last week, the policy-making General Synod of the Church of
England voted to proceed with draft legislation to admit women to
the priesthood, rejecting Runcie's advice not to do so because it
might split the church. England could have its first woman priest
by 1993 if Parliament agrees.
   Runcie warned that women's ordination could be an added
hindrance to unity with the Roman Catholic and Orthodox churches,
which have all-male priesthoods.
   The draft rules propose compensating clergymen with payments up
to about $50,000 if they quit the church because they feel they
cannot work with women priests.
   England's Movement for the Ordination of Women says that about
1,000 women have been ordained, most of them in the United States,
Canada and New Zealand. Opponents say the true figure is about 700.
   Churchmen opposed to women priests on grounds of scripture and
tradition say while they might eventually accept them, they would
never accept a woman bishop because bishops are followers of the
apostles of Jesus Christ, founder of Christianity, who were all men.
   Runcie has warned that because some bishops would not tolerate
women bishops, the Anglican Communion might divide into a
federation of loosely linked regional churches, each with its own
conference to replace the Lambeth Conference.
   ``We have lost members because of the ordination of women, and
we still have members who are distressed about it,'' said
Memphis-based U.S. Episcopalian Bishop Alex Dickson of the Diocese
of West Tennessee, when he arrived in Canterbury.
   ``I am concerned that we remain sensitive to people who oppose
women's ordination and that we make room for them.''
   The first Lambeth Conference was held in 1867 and attended by 76
bishops, at Lambeth Palace, official London residence of the
archbishop of Canterbury.
   Runcie has personally invited each of the 577 bishops to the
12th Lambeth Conference. About 380 of them have said they will
bring their wives, who will hold their own conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880716-0018 </DOCNO>
