<DOCNO> AP880716-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Airliner-Hostages     07-16 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-Hostages,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airliner Attack Interrupted Hostage Talks, Magazine Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner-UN, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lebanese magazine says the U.S. Navy's
missile attack on an Iranian jetliner derailed hostage talks
between the United States and Iran.
   Ash-Shiraa said Friday that talks between negotiatiors for the
two countries had been held in a European country and ``covered
many details.''
   The report said ``a number of American hostages were to be
released in south Beirut in return for a public change in the
American political stand on the Gulf War in favor of Iran.''
   It said the talks in Europe broke down after the Navy shot down
the Iran Air jetliner July 3, killing all 290 people on board. The
United States said its forces mistook the plane for a jet fighter.
   The report carried no further details of the alleged talks and
cited no sources.
   Ash-Shiraa gained international fame in 1986 when it broke the
story of secret U.S. arms sales to Iran to win release of American
hostages. But the magazine's recent reports on the 18 foreign
captives held in Lebanon have not been accurate.
   In a separate report, the magazine said members of a West German
delegation held talks in Christian east Beirut with representatives
of a pro-Iranian group holding West German hostage Rudolf Cordes.
   ``The German delegation has returned home after the talks
reached a dead end,'' the report said. The magazine did not report
the cause of the impasse.
   Cordes, 53, a businessman with Hoechst AG, a West German
chemical firm, was kidnapped Jan. 17, 1987 in Moslem west Beirut.
The pro-Iranian Holy Warriors for Freedom claimed responsibility
for his abduction.
   Nine Americans are among the foreign captives in Lebanon. The
longest-held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for
The Associated Press. He was abducted March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
