<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Politics-Quotes     07-16 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Politics-Quotes,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quotes From the Presidential Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments from the presidential
campaign trail:
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, ruling out Jesse Jackson's notion to have
former President Jimmy Carter play play peacemaker in their
pre-convention disagreements: ``We don't need mediators.''
   
   JIMMY CARTER, saying he thinks Dukakis and Jackson can work out
their differences on their own, without his help: ``I don't think
they need any mediation. I think what is needed is to just have a
better means of communication between one another.''
   
   WALTER MONDALE, former Democratic presidential candidate,
warning against heightened tensions between Dukakis and Jackson:
``We always have rising tensions about this time; it's inherent.
... But I believe this is a year where Democrats understand these
fights, if they're carried on too far, become too personalized,
they set poison down into the roots that can be difficult to deal
with.''
   
   JESSE JACKSON, preaching accommodation rather than discord: ``We
simply cannot win without each other. We can only win with each
other. It is in our distinct advantage to find common ground.''
   
   BOB DOLE, saying the wide gap that exists between the outlook of
Dukakis and his vice presidential running mate will not occur on
the Republican ticket: ``You're going to find only shades of
difference in our philosophy, not this chasm you find between
Dukakis on the one hand and Lloyd Bentsen on the other.''
</TEXT>
