<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-US     07-16 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-US,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Vietnam Agree On Resettling Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam could begin allowing political
prisoners to emigrate to the United States in the next several
months, Vietnam's official news agency said today.
   The Vietnam News Agency quoted a statement by U.S. and
Vietnamese negotiators as saying that the two nations reached
preliminary agreement on releasing prisoners from so-called
``re-education'' camps.
   The joint statement said that while further talks are needed,
``both sides are hopeful that the processing of released detainees
can begin within the next several months,'' the news agency said.
   The agency, monitored in Bangkok, said the statement was issued
Friday after two days of talks in Hanoi between teams led by
Vietnam's deputy foreign minister, Tran Quang Co, and Robert L.
Funseth, U.S. senior deputy assistant secretary of state for
refugee programs.
   The statement said Funseth reaffirmed President Reagan's 1984
commitment to welcome for resettlement former detainees and their
families who had close ties with the United States or its ally, the
South Vietnamese government.
   Co in turn reaffirmed Vietnam's policy to let these people
emigrate, it said.
   Vietnam had demanded that the United States guarantee that the
former prisoners would not be allowed to conduct anti-Vietnamese
activities once they were resettled. Vietnam has accused U.S.
authorities of helping Vietnamese emigres seeking to overthrow the
communist government.
   The Vietnamese side reaffirmed that Vietnam will not encourage
them to engage in anti-U.S. activities, the news agency said.
   The United States ended its combat role in the Vietnam War in
1973. In 1975, South Vietnam fell to the communist forces of North
Vietnam and the two Vietnams were reunited under a communist
government.
   The statement said the U.S. team ``declared that the released
re-education center detainees coming to the United States would be
subject to all U.S. laws, including those affecting the activities
of U.S. residents toward other countries.''
   The joint statement said the two sides discussed ways of
speeding the processing of applications of former prisoners. A
limited number of former prisoners have gone to the United States
through the United Nations-sponsored Orderly Departure Program,
under which Vietnamese refugees and migrants leave their homeland
on regular flights.
   The North Vietnamese communists established the huge network of
re-education camps, which usually combined manual labor with
ideological study, after defeating South Vietnam in April 1975.
   The U.S. State Department estimates that about 900,000 former
U.S. government employees or South Vietnamese officials have spent
time in the camps, which the human rights group Amnesty
International has condemned but Vietnam has called lenient
punishment for ``war criminals.''
   The United States renewed it interest in the prisoners after
Nguyen Van Linh, the pragmatic Communist Party chief, urged
national reconciliation and freed hundreds of former South
Vietnamese officials in September 1987 and February this year.
   Vice Minister of Information Phan Quang said on Feb. 11 that
only 150 former officials remained held.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
