<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     07-16 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says Rebels Violated Truce In Three Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Contras, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra rebels violating a truce with
the Sandinista government attacked three times in northern and
central Nicaragua, and one civilian and three rebels were killed,
the Defense Ministry said.
   The statement Friday said nothing of any government casualties.
The U.S.-backed rebels and the leftist government have accused each
other of truce violations on and off since the cease-fire began
March 21.
   The ministry said that in one of the attacks on Thursday, three
Contras died in a shootout with an army patrol in northern
Matagalpa province.
   It also said the Contras ambushed an army truck in northern
Jinotega province, kidnapping 16 people on board, and that four
other people were abducted by the rebels and a civilian was killed
in central Chontales province.
   The Sandinistas celebrate nine years in power next Tuesday. The
insurrection they led in July 1979 ended 42 years of rule by the
rightist, pro-American Somoza dynasty.
   Representatives from both sides have held meetings to try to
reach a peace accord without success. The last round of talks in
June ended in deadlock and no new meetings were scheduled.
   The army announced on Friday a series of military exercises to
defend Managua, the capital, in case of attack. The Sandinistas
have long claimed the United States eventually plans to invade
Nicaragua.
   On Monday, the Sandinistas expelled U.S. Ambassador Richard
Melton and seven other U.S. diplomats, accusing them of conspiring
to undermine the government.
   The Interior Ministry announced Friday night the suspension of
the radio program ``El Despertar'' (The Awakening) for
``transmitting false information.'' The statement, read over
state-run radio, did not say how long the suspension would be in
effect.
   Last week the government closed down the Roman Catholic Church's
Radio Catolica; suspended publication for 15 days of the only
opposition newspaper, La Prensa, and this week expropriated Ingenio
San Antonio, the country's leading sugar refinery.
   Business leaders called the takeover of the company, belonging
to the wealthy Pellas family, a setback for private enterprise.
   Washington reacted to the expulsion of U.S. diplomats by
ordering out Nicaraguan Ambassador Carlos Tunnermann and seven
embassy colleagues.
   Tunnermann reluctantly bowed to the order and departed on
Friday, five minutes ahead of the deadline imposed by the State
Department.
   In Managua, Foreign Minister Miguel D'Escoto issued a statement
saying Tunnermann would remain as Nicaragua's ambassador to the
Organization of American States in Washington ``until this
controversy can be elucidated.''
   The statement reiterated Nicaragua's position that as OAS
ambassador, Tunnermann cannot be barred from Washington despite his
expulsion as ambassador to the United States.
   Nicaragua called on the InterAmerican Legal Committee to resolve
the dispute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
