<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Teamsters 1stLd-Writethru a0410 07-16 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0410,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New President: Condolences, Not Congratulations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to fix grammar, 2nd graf to delete comma after
``Boston'' and 16th graf to indicate Charlestown is section of
Boston sted Charlestown, Mass.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rejecting Jackie Presser's choice of an heir,
the Teamsters are returning power to one of its veteran ``old
guard'' East Coast leaders at a time when the union is under siege
both from without and within.
   The Teamsters' 17-member executive board on Friday elected
William J. McCarthy, 69, of Boston to succeed the late Presser as
president of the 1.6-million-member union.
   McCarthy, who has headed the Teamsters' operations in New
England for the past two decades, beat out Secretary-Treasurer
Weldon Mathis, 62, of Atlanta, by a 9-8 vote, said several sources.
   Presser, who died a week ago after being incapacitated most of
the past 18 months with cancer, had named Mathis in 1985 to the
union's No. 2 post and appointed him interim president in May, just
before Presser was to undergo brain surgery.
   The struggle for the top post was the most contentious, and most
open, in the union's 85-year history.
   Behind McCarthy's successful challenge was veteran Teamster
power broker Joseph Trerotola of New York, at 70 the union's
longest-standing vice president and head of its 15-state Eastern
Conference since 1969.
   ``The Presser forces lined up behind Mathis and the Trerotola
forces lined up with McCarthy,'' said one source, who, like the
others, would talk about the wrangling for power only on the
condition of anonymity.
   Mathis remains the union's secretary-treasurer.
   The turnover at the top of the nation's largest union occurs
just two weeks after the Justice Department filed suit to seize
control of its affairs, claiming the entire Teamsters leadership
has been corrupted by organized crime figures.
   McCarthy's election also reflects wide-scale disenchantment with
the recently negotiated National Master Freight Agreement, the
union's biggest contract covering 200,000 Teamsters in the
interstate trucking industry.
   The three-year accord negotiated under Mathis' leadership during
Presser's absence was rejected by 64 percent of the rank-and-file
members casting ballots in a ratification vote last spring.
   However, under the Teamsters' constitution, it takes a
two-thirds membership vote to nullify an accord once it is
initialed by the union's negotiators.
   McCarthy, breaking from past Teamster traditions to keep
disputes within the union's hierarchy behind closed doors, actively
campaigned against the freight accord.
   Upon his election Friday, he indicated he will try to reopen the
trucking industry contract for new negotiations.
   ``I don't know what I can do but I plan to do everything I can
to improve on it and get the wishes of our membership,'' he said.
   McCarthy has presided over the 8,000-member Teamsters Local 25
the Charlestown section of Boston for 33 years and headed the
international union's operations in New England for two decades.
   Asked by a reporter Friday what Presser would have thought about
his election, McCarthy confirmed his reputation among leaders of
other labor unions as being a tough bargainer _ and possessing a
quick temper.
   ``Who knows? Maybe he would roll over in his grave,'' he
replied. ``I don't know what he was thinking. Why don't you try to
locate him. That's a goofy question, I'll give you a goofy answer.''
   McCarthy declined to elaborate on the power struggle with Mathis.
   ``The great strength of this board is that we will argue and
fight about an issue but when the majority vote is taken, everyone
stands behind the decision,'' he said.
   However, at least two union board members objected to declaring
the vote for McCarthy unanimous, a Teamster tradition when the
mantle is passed from one president to another, one source said.
   Both McCarthy and Mathis are viewed by leaders of other unions
as being ``clean'' _ with no major ties to organized crime figures
in contrast to the ties that the government alleges that Presser
and former Teamster presidents Roy Williams and Jimmy Hoffa had.
   Other than being listed as a defendant like all of the Teamster
vice presidents in the federal suit to take over the union,
McCarthy's name surfaced only once in the 200 pages of documents
the government filed two weeks ago to support its takeover case.
   In a transcript of an FBI-wiretapped conversation on May 9,
1984, convicted New York crime boss Anthony Salerno is quoted as
recognizing McCarthy's name as the Teamsters' ``head boss of the
East Coast.''
   Salerno was quoted as saying in the tapped telephone
conversation with John Tronolone, a reputed Cleveland organized
crime figure, that McCarthy is ``very friendly'' with a man that
Salerno identified only as Cass.
   In view of the government's unprecedented attempt to take over
the entire union, McCarthy said Friday he has a ``tough job ahead.''
   ``It should be condolences, not congratulations,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
