<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0205EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Contras Bjt   07-16 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contras, Bjt,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Gather in Attempt to Patch Differences</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Retransmitting a0441 to fix cycle designator</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOSE ALDUEY SIERRA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan rebels,
shaken by U.S. aid reductions and dissidents demanding more
democracy within the Contra movement, are seeking to reorganize the
Nicaraguan Resistance.
   Leaders of the Contras from Miami, Venezuela, Costa Rica and
other points will meet in the Concorde Hotel on Sunday and Monday
to resolve issues that threaten to split the rebels fighting the
leftist Sandinista government.
   Nicaraguan Ambassador Danilo Valle said his government was
disturbed that the Dominican government would allow ``groups and
people who not more than two days ago threatened to commit
terrorist acts and assassination attempts against Sandinista
government leaders to come here to organize themselves.''
   Dominican Foreign Minister Favio Herrera said the meeting would
be a ``private affair'' and the government would not permit the
Contra leaders ``to issue extemporaneous declarations beyond those
strictly related to the private character of the meeting that might
affect the cordial relationship maintained with the Nicaraguan
government.''
   The Nicaraguan Resistance groups several different
anti-Sandinista forces following the dissolution of the umbrella
organization National Union of Opposition over a year ago.
   Adolfo Calero heads the conservatives, Azucena Ferrey the
Christian Democrats, Adolfo Robledo the Social Democrats, Aristides
Sanchez the liberals, and Alfredo Salazar the southern opposition.
Col. Enrique Bermudez heads the labor, agrarian and business
sectors as well as the Miskito Indians, and Pedro Joaquin Chamorro
represents the ``independent'' sector.
   According to the organization's by-laws, each group can send
seven delegates to the meeting.
   The five members of the organization's directorate are expected
to be either replaced or ratified in their positions.
   The five are Calero, Salazar, Ferrey, Sanchez and Chamorro.
   Dissident Contra commanders, backed by Calero and Chamorro, have
demanded the removal of Bermudez as military chief. They accuse the
former National Guard colonel of being inefficient, corrupt and too
close to supporters of Anastasio Somoza, the right-wing dictator
ousted by the Sandinistas in 1979.
   The dissidents have been booted out of Honduras and lost their
commands. Since then Calero and Chamorro have rarely been seen with
Sanchez, Cesar and Ferrey.
   The possibility of renewed aid surfaced Thursday after the
Sandinistas violently broke up a non-violent demonstration in
Managua, closed a Catholic radio station and the opposition
newspaper La Prensa, arrested 40 opposition leaders and expelled
U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton.
   In a show of bipartisan unity, the U.S. Senate approved Thursday
a non-binding resolution warning Nicaragua's government that
military aid to the Contras could resume unless it reverses what it
described as ``dramatic new steps in brutality'' against its own
citizens.
   In what some senators called a ``carrot and stick policy,''
adopted on a 91-4 vote, the Senate also said it was ready to extend
U.S. economic aid to Nicaragua if the Sandinistas fully comply with
commitments made a year ago and ``proceed to permit the
establishment of a democratic system.''
   The Contras normally once had six directors. One of the seats
has been empty since Alfonso Robelo quit and moved permanently to
Central America.
   Sources speaking on condition of anonymity say Calero, whose
brother Mario was just indicted in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. for
illegally supplying mercenaries to the Contras, may also resign or
be voted out of his post, and it is possible Chamorro would go with
him.
   The dissidents have proposed as a compromise that Bermudez be
bumped up to the empty director's seat, getting him out of the
military command without humiliating him, but the directors have
never endorsed that idea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880716-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Shultz     07-16 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Says World Pressure Will Prevent Olympic Terrorism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and Chinese pressure on North
Korea will help prevent terrorist attacks on the 1988 Olympics,
U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz said today.
   ``I think everybody will be exerting their influence in a
positive way. I feel that the Olympics will go off in good style,''
he told newsmen shortly before landing in the South Korean capital
en route from Beijing.
   He said the South Koreans were also ``doing such a fine job in
putting into place all the measures that deter any kinds of
disturbances.''
   But on the eve of Shultz's arrival, the United Nations Command
accused North Korea of trying to undermine the games.
   ``Your attempts to contrive an atmosphere of danger on the
Korean peninsula, in a transparent attempt to undermine the
upcoming Seoul Olympics, will not succeed,'' said U.S. Rear Adm.
William T. Pendley, chief UNC delegate to the Military Armistice
Commission.
   Arriving for his seventh stop on a nine-country Asian and
Pacific visit, Shultz was driven straight from the airport to the
Olympic Village and Olympic Park.
   He toured the living quarters at the Olympic Village, which will
house up to 15,000 athletes and officials during the Sept. 17 to
Oct. 2 event. He also was driven through one of two major sports
complexes studded with futuristic stadiums and outdoor sculptures.
   The electronic scoreboard flashed a welcome message when Shultz
and his party entered the main, 10,000-seat swimming stadium.
   Olympic security is one of the key issues Shultz is expected to
discuss when he meets President Roh Tae-woo, Foreign Minister Choi
Kwang-soo and other South Korean government and opposition leaders.
   Also scheduled for discussion are South Korea's recent
initiatives at reconciliation with North Korea, U.S.-Korean trade
problems and America's continuing military role in South Korea.
   He called President Roh's recent proposal to ease tensions with
North Korea as ``a very important step.
   ``It's too bad the North Koreans brushed it off. It may well be
that they will take a second look,'' Shultz told reporters.
   He said the United States would have to carefully assess North
Korean actions in light of Seoul's initiatives. Shultz said
U.S.-North Korean relations had been moving in a positive direction
until the destruction of a South Korean passenger airliner Nov. 29
near Burma, with the deaths of all 115 people aboard.
   North Korea denied all involvement in the alleged bombing.
   In remarks to reporters before arriving in Seoul, Shultz said
that in preparing for the Olympiad the South Koreans were alert to
the placement of surface-to-air missiles within range of Seoul and
the recent introduction of an advanced Soviet warplane in North
Korea.
   The Soviet Union, according to Washington, last year provided
North Korea with SAM-5 missiles and more recently a small number of
advanced MIG-29 jets.
   But Shultz also stressed that Moscow has ``flatly'' said the
North Koreans would not interfere with the Olympic Games, which
they are boycotting after failing to become co-hosts of the event.
   Shultz said he had received similar assurances from the Chinese,
who like the Soviets, will be competing in the Olympics.
   During his trip to Seoul, Shultz may run into some criticism in
discussing U.S.-South Korean trade relations.
   The United States has urged economically booming South Korea to
liberalize its regulations on some U.S.imports to offset a trade
deficit running at about $10 billion.
</TEXT>
