<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mandela     07-16 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mandela,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mandelas Cancel Birthday Reunion In Protest Gesture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of jailed black
leader Nelson Mandela says she wants to focus attention on other
victims of apartheid and has spurned a government offer to visit
her husband on his 70th birthday.
   Winnie Mandela decided to spend the day at home on Monday rather
than accept the offer of a six-hour visit with her husband, who has
been jailed for 26 years, said family lawyer Ismail Ayob.
   ``She has taken this decision as both she and Mr. Mandela have
never sought any special privileges for themselves,'' he said
Friday.
   The visit would have been the longest reunion with Mandela,
leader of the outlawed African National Congress, since he was
jailed in 1962 for leaving South Africa illegally and inciting
unrest.
   While serving a five-year term, Mandela was sentenced to life in
prison in 1964 for sabotage and conspiracy to overthrow the
government.
   The government confirmed the cancellation of the visit.
   Ayob said the Mandelas' decision was meant to ``focus attention
on the tens of thousands of mothers, sisters and daughters and to
the fathers, brothers and sons who have never had the privilege of
spending the day with their loved ones who remain in incarceration
for their opposition to apartheid.''
   The government, meanwhile, has been cracking down on various
events scheduled to honor Mandela on his birthday.
   Activists in Cape Town said 11 blacks organizing a sports
festval to commemorate Mandela's birthday were arrested Friday,
raising to about 25 the number of people detained in the area in
connection with the planned birthday celebrations.
   The government also has banned a huge charity concert planned
for Sunday near Soweto, Johannesburg's main black township. The
action was denounced as ``silly, vindictive and spiteful'' by Helen
Suzman, a parliament member for the anti-apartheid Progressive
Federal Party.
   Organizers in Cape Town said they would go ahead with a concert
on Sunday, planned for an indoor hall to avoid restrictions on
outdoor gatherings. But an indoor concert planned in Durban also
has been banned by police.
   Sports events are not covered by the restrictions. The Cape Town
activists said they did not know why police had detained the
organizers of a sports festival scheduled for today in Guguletu, a
black township.
   The Western Cape Teachers Union said its posters promoting a
Mandela tribute Friday night had been covered by stickers saying
``Cancelled.'' Hundreds of anonymous pamphlets criticizing Mandela
appeared overnight in the mixed-race township of Athlone.
   Under security regulations, organizers of all outdoor events
except sports activities and funerals must obtain permission from
authorities.
   Huge celebrations are also planned in London and Amsterdam this
weekend to commemorate Mandela's birthday.
   Numerous foreign governments, meanwhile, issued messages Friday
in honor of Mandela's birthday.
   Among those calling for Mandela's release were West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, British Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe
and Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney.
   Foreign ministers of Denmark, Finland, Iceland, Norway and
Sweden sent a message to Mandela on Friday saying they would press
for his release.
   The Italian government in Pretoria said it imported a copy of
Bernardo Bertolucci's film, ``The Last Emperor,'' because Mandela
wanted to see it. The Prison Service said it had not been informed
of any plans to deliver the film to Pollsmoor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
