<1ST_LINE>r a PM-911Rape     07-16 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-911 Rape,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rape Victim Sues City Over 911</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was raped inside her home by an
intruder while police searched outside and left says the city
knowingly operated a flawed 911 telephone emergency system that
resulted in the attack.
   The woman and her husband made the charge in a lawsuit filed
against the city Friday in Allegheny County Common Pleas Court.
Their names were not disclosed.
   The lawsuit contends the city failed to adequately screen and
train employees for its 911 communications center and failed to
correct procedures ``so deficient that the continued maintenance of
them was outrageous and shocking to the conscience.''
   The woman's attorney, Jan Swensen, said the city advised
residents to dial 911 for emergency help and then failed to provide
that help.
   City Public Safety Director Glenn Cannon and city Solicitor Dan
Pellegrini declined to comment on the lawsuit.
   After an investigation, Cannon ordered 911 operators to pass on
detailed information about emergency calls and to question police
about how they resolve calls before officers are permitted to leave
the scene.
   Cannon also reprimanded five police officers and three 911
workers for failing to respond properly.
   The woman told police she dialed 911 at about 11:15 p.m. on Feb.
2 after she heard someone trying to break into her second-story
apartment in the city's Point Breeze neighborhood.
   While she was talking to the 911 operator, officials said a man
with a knife burst into the room and tore the telephone cord from
the wall. The 911 operator thought the woman had hung up, officials
said.
   When the intruder saw police walking around the house and heard
them knocking on her door, he threatened the woman and said he had
``nothing further to lose and that he might as well rape'' her, the
woman said.
   Police searched outside for several minutes and left,
authorities said. They didn't break down the woman's door because
911 operators failed to tell them that the woman reported the
break-in herself and that the call abruptly broke off, authorities
said.
   Police have made no arrests in the attack.
</TEXT>
