<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TreasureRuling     07-16 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasure Ruling,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Against Treasure Hunters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ruled that a sunken 17th
century Spanish galleon found a year ago belongs to the state of
Florida, not the two men who have claimed it and up to $500,000 in
booty.
   Under Friday's ruling, Peter Leo and Dominic Addario of Jupiter
would have to surrender the treasure, including 2,500 gold and
silver coins, a large silver bar dated 1652, a small gold bar and
several cannons.
   The treasure, worth $300,000 to $500,000, will remain in the
hands of a conservator while the ruling is appealed. U.S. District
Judge Stanley Marcus banned any other salvagers from taking
artifacts from the wreck in Jupiter Inlet.
   The two men, who have incorporated under the name Jupiter Wreck,
Inc., discovered the sunken galleon last summer buried in the sand
about 100 yards off the inlet's beach.
   Last August the state Department of Natural Resources sought an
injuction to stop them from exploiting the galleon. The department
said the wreck belonged to the state and the men needed a license
to remove anything.
   Leo, 33, and Addario, 39, represented by attorney David Horan,
who also worked for Key West treasure hunter Mel Fisher in a score
of similar actions, countered by seeking an injuction barring the
state from interfering with them, but Marcus ruled against them.
   Horan said Marcus' decision contradicted previous rulings by
Chief U.S. District Judge James Lawrence King in a Fisher case, and
that he would appeal it to the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
