<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mrs.Letterman     07-16 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mrs. Letterman,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Found Incompetent To Stand Trial Second Time In Letterman
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who claimed to be David
Letterman's wife will undergo psychiatric treatment before a judge
considers for the third time whether she is competent to face
charges that she broke into the TV talk show host's home and stole
his car.
   Superior Court Judge James Bingham on Friday ordered 36-year-old
Margaret Ray, of no known address, to return to court Oct. 14 for
reconsideration of his second finding that she is incompetent to
stand trial.
   Bingham ordered the woman to undergo six months of psychiatric
treatment in the state hospital where she has been a patient for
the past several weeks.
   The judge ruled last month that although Ray could understand
the charges, she was unable to assist in her defense. She has been
held in lieu of $25,000 bail and treated at Fairfield Hills
Hospital.
   Bingham allowed another psychiatric examination after Ray
objected to the first report by a doctor who found she was
``delusional.''
   The second psychiatrist, Sander H. Fogle of Fairfield Hills,
told Bingham on Friday that he also believed Ray couldn't assist in
her defense.
   Fogle testified that Ray would be helped by six months of
psychotherapy and lithium treatments.
   Police allege that Ray broke into Letterman's New Canaan home in
May while he was out of town and lived there for several days
before stealing his car.
   She was arrested May 22 at a Lincoln Tunnel toll booth in
Weehawken, N.J. Authorities became suspicious when the woman and
her 3-year-old son drove up in Letterman's 1988 Porsche 911 but
couldn't pay the $3 toll.
   Ray told police she was Letterman's wife and the boy was the NBC
talk-show host's son.
   Three days later she was released from jail after Letterman
asked police to drop the charges. That afternoon she allegedly
again broke into Letterman's house. Ray faces two counts of
second-degree burglary and one count of first-degree larceny.
</TEXT>
