<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HowardBeach     07-16 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Howard Beach,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Acquitted, Three Guilty Of Charges In Racial Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury in the final trial stemming from the
Howard Beach racial attack found three of the four defendants
guilty of misdemeanor riot charges but acquitted them all of felony
charges.
   William Bollander, Thomas Farino and James Povinelli, all 18,
were found guilty Friday of second-degree riot, punishable by up to
a year in prison. They were acquitted of first-degree riot, a
felony that carries a maximum sentence of four years.
   John Saggese, 20, was found innocent of both counts.
   The case stemmed from the Dec. 20, 1986, attack by a white gang
on three blacks in the Howard Beach section of Queens. One of the
blacks, Michael Griffith, 23, was killed when struck by a car as he
fled the gang.
   ``I'll deal with it, that's all. I'm going to beat this,''
Bollander said after the verdict.
   ``I prayed,'' said Saggese. Displaying a small religious object,
he said, ``I had my hand on this the whole time.''
   Saggese said he told his friends and co-defendants, ``I'm sorry.
   ``I feel a year and a half of torture is over for me, but not my
friends. They're not guilty, but we're going to stick together.''
   Friends and relatives wept and embraced as the guilty verdicts
were read, then cheered at Saggese's acquittal.
   The verdict came after the jury said it was deadlocked earlier
in the day, prompting the government to offer a plea bargain of
youthful offender status and probation, according to sources on
both sides of the case. The offer was rejected.
   ``To the day I die, I'll know I did the right thing,'' said
Bollander, fighting back tears, referring to the decision to reject
the plea bargain.
   Bollander's attorney, Todd D. Greenberg, said all three will
file an appeal immediately after their Sept. 14 sentencing. But
Richard La Rosa, attorney for Farino, said, ``We'll have to see.
It's an expensive process.''
   The jury told state Supreme Court Justice Thomas Demakos in a
noontime note: ``We are not at an impasse. We are against a
mountain.''
   Demakos, however, noted that there had been five weeks of
testimony, and said, ``This is far too an important matter ... for
you, after a trial of this length, simply to throw in the sponge. I
ask that you reason with each other and listen to reason.''
   Griffith's mother said after the verdict, ``Now is not for
rejoicing. Now is for prayer.''
   On Thursday, a separate jury in the case cleared Thomas
Gucciardo, 19, of all charges, including attempted murder. The jury
foreman said the defendant had not been positively identified.
   Three youths were convicted of manslaughter in December in the
attack, and a fourth youth was acquitted. Two other teen-agers
pleaded guilty to felony riot charges just prior to the second
trial.
   Felony riot involves ``tumultuous and violent conduct'' by a
group of more than 10 people. Misdemeanor or second-degree riot
involves such conduct by a group of more than four people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
