<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Hotel Fire,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Dead, Several Tourists Injured In Hotel Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire devasted a hotel in northern Paris early
today, killing four people and injuring several more, including
American, West German, British and Belgian tourists, police said.
   The names of the foreigners injured in the blaze were not made
public, and officials said the four dead had not been identified.
   The fire started at about 3:30 a.m. on the fourth floor of the
Hotel St. Vincent de Paul on rue d'Hauteville, in a run-down
neighborhood a few blocks from the Gare du Nord train station.
   By the time firemen got it under control, the building was
nearly in ruins. Fire officials said the cause of the fire was not
known, but appeared to be accidental.
   The manager of the hotel, Bernard Bonhomme, was among the
injured taken to a hospital for treatment. The others were not
identified.
