<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0619EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AmtrakCrash     07-16 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amtrak Crash,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Engineer Sentenced In Federal Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE FITZHENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former Conrail engineer who caused an
Amtrak crash that killed 16 people faces three more years in prison
for conspiring to obstruct an investigation of the accident, the
worst in Amtrak history.
   Rick L. Gates is already serving a five-year prison sentence on
a state charge of manslaughter by locomotive. The federal term
ordered Friday by U.S. District Judge Norman Ramsey will be served
consecutively.
   Gates drove three linked Conrail engines through a closed track
switch and into the path of a high-speed Amtrak passenger train
near Chase, Md., in January 1987. The accident also left 175 people
injured.
   Gates, 34, of suburban Essex was charged April 1 in federal
court with four counts, including conspiracy, obstruction of an
agency investigation and two counts of making false statements to
investigators from the National Transportation Safety Board.
   Gates pleaded guilty in May to conspiracy for lying to NTSB
investigators about following safety procedures and smoking
marijuana with his brakeman before the crash. Prosecutors agreed to
dismiss the other charges.
   The brakeman, Edward Cromwell, was granted immunity from federal
and state prosecutors for his cooperation in the case.
   The prosecution sought the maximum sentence, five years in
prison. Gates' attorney had requested that Gates be sentenced to
two or three years in prison, with all but six months suspended,
and supervised probation after he is released.
   Relatives of victims said Gates' sentence was not as important
as federal legislation to mandate drug and alcohol testing of
transportation workers.
   ``I don't want to be Mr. Gates' judge. I think we need to focus
on finding the next 10 or 20 Ricky Gates out there before they kill
people,'' said Roger Horn of Baltimore, whose 16-year-old daughter
was killed in the crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
