<DOCNO> AP880716-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0621EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i India-UnionCarbide     07-16 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>India-Union Carbide,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Judge Issues Summons For Former Carbide Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bhopal magistrate today issued a fourth
summons for former Union Carbide Corp. Chairman Warren Anderson to
appear in court on criminal charges stemming from the 1984 Bhopal
gas disaster.
   Kanhaiya Lal Sisodia, chief Bhopal judicial magistrate, approved
the summons after a government lawyer complained earlier papers
were not served because Anderson and Union Carbide were ``trying to
avoid being prosecuted in India.
   ``How can the marriage procession go ahead without the
bridegroom?'' government attorney U.S. Prasad told a hearing in
this central Indian city.
   Sisodia also ordered Robert Kennedy, now chairman of the
Danbury, Conn.-based corporation, to appear in court here Sept. 24
in connection with the criminal charge against Union Carbide.
   Kennedy was not named as a defendant when the case was filed in
December.
   The criminal charge against Union Carbide, Anderson and other
company officers is one of four legal actions filed before Indian
courts stemming from a massive leak of lethal gas on Dec. 3, 1984,
from a pesticide plant run by a Carbide subsidiary.
   Nearly 3,000 people were killed and at least 20,000 seriously
injured in what is regarded as the world's worst industrial
accident.
   The criminal charges accuse Carbide and the others of homicide
and causing injury. Before today, the court had issued three
summonses for Anderson.
   Prasad, attorney for the Central Bureau of Investigation, the
Indian equivalent of the American FBI, said the papers could not be
served because ``Union Carbide is suppressing his address in the
U.S.A.''
   Anderson has not been located depite the efforts of the Indian
Foreign Ministry and Interpol, Prasad said.
   The former Carbide chairman came to India at the time of the
1984 disaster and was arrested and jailed. But he was freed on
$1,785 bail put up by the accountant of the subsidiary, Union
Carbide of India Limited.
   Sisodia ordered accountant A.M. Kuruvila to appear in court
after Prasad argued bail papers required Kuruvila to present
Anderson in court when required.
   In addition to the criminal charges, the Indian government has
filed a $3 billion civil damage suit maintaining negligence by
Union Carbide caused the gas leak. Union Carbide argues the leak
resulted from sabotage by a disgruntled employee.
   The two sides also are arguing in the Indian courts over a $270
million interim judgment for damages against Carbide. India
maintains the amount is not enough. Carbide says the ruling amounts
to a pre-judgment before the case is actually decided.
   In addition, Madhya Pradesh state, where Bhopal is located, has
filed a suit accusing Union Carbide of contempt of court for its
request that the judge hearing the damage suit remove himself from
the case because of bias.
   District Judge M.W. Deo turned down the request, denying any
bias.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
