<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0707EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FrozenBoy     07-16 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Frozen Boy,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Dies After His Frozen Body Revived</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-year-old boy who was revived after he fell
into a freezer while searching for Popsicles never regained
consciousness and later died.
   Doctors said Friday it was a miracle the youth had even been
resuscitated. ``We've never had anyone survive so long. This is
what makes it so unusual,'' said Dr. Stephen Evans of St. Joseph
Hospital in Lorain.
   The heartbeat and body temperature of 8-year-old Joseph Krogg
were restored by doctors several hours after the boy arrived at the
hospital Thursday night, but he made no further progress. He was
airlifted to Rainbow Babies' and Children's Hospital in Cleveland,
where he died at 4:02 p.m. Friday.
   ``He was put on life support, and he never regained
consciousness,'' said Jane Yousey, a Rainbow spokeswoman.
   The youth was reported missing by his parents about 5 p.m.
Thursday, said Detective Sgt. Joe Monia of the Sheffield Lake
Police Department. His father, Dale Krogg, found him at 6:30 p.m.
when he went to the freezer in the garage to get meat for dinner.
   Joseph apparently fell into the freezer while trying to reach
some Popsicles, and the lid closed and latched, Monia said.
   Evans had told Krogg that the chances of resuscitating his son
were one in a million.
   Doctors warmed Joseph's body, on which icicles had formed, by
running tubes of warm saline through his stomach and bladder and
wrapping him in electric blankets.
   About 11 p.m. Thursday, Joseph's heart began to beat again, and
by 1 a.m. Friday he had a strong pulse, adequate blood pressure and
his temperature returned to normal, Evans said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
