<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0836EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0485endearlyintheafternoon
07-16 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0507</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Thunderstorms Swirl Over Much Of The Nation</BYLINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `In Kansas ...' to RESTORE dropped
`winds.' Minneapolis, Kan., is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled over much of the nation today after hot,
moist and unstable air from the Gulf of Mexico clashed with a cold
front from Kansas to Wisconsin to whip up tornadoes, damaging
winds, hail and rain.
   In Nebraska, three tornadoes were reported in the Omaha and
Council Bluffs areas Friday, damaging more than 100 homes and
flipping railroad cars. Trees and power lines were damaged or
downed in Omaha.
   In Kansas, the same line of thunderstorms spawned a tornado near
Wakefield; caused 55 to 60 mph winds at Abilene; produced damaging
winds at Minneapolis, and blasted Ellsworth with 1}-inch hail.
   Thunderstorms swirling through Wisconsin and Minnesota ripped
down trees and brought hail nearly 2 inches in diameter.
Thunderstorms also produced damaging winds in portions of Indiana
and Michigan.
   In lower Michigan, Kent County was pummeled by 1{-inch hail. A
building roof was destroyed and several trees were damaged in Emmet
County.
   In Florida, tornadoes touched down at Tarpon Springs, where
there was damage to several unoccupied trailer homes. Two tornadoes
were reported near Palatka.
   Today's forecast called for rain and thunderstorms from northern
and central New England across inland New York, through Florida and
the central Gulf of Mexico coast; showers and thunderstorms
scattered over northern Indiana and northern Illinois, and
generally sunny weather over the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s and 80s over northern
New England, inland New York, Michigan, Wisconsin and from
Minnesota across the northern tier of states through Washington
into northern Oregon; in the 70s and 80s along the California
coast; the upper 90s and 100 degrees from southern West Virginia
across southern Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Kentucky, Tennessee,
northern Georgia, much of Mississippi, Kansas, central Texas,
western Colorado and northern Utah; near 115 degrees through the
desert Southwest, and in the 90s through the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 49
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 97 degrees at
Glendale, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 81 fair; Boston 67 fair; Buffalo 74 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 80 foggy; Cincinnati 83 fair; Cleveland 81 cloudy;
Detroit 77 cloudy; Miami 78 fair; New York 72 foggy; Philadelphia
72 foggy; Pittsburgh 75 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine 61 partly
cloudy; Washington 79 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 59 fair; Chicago 85 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
84 fair; Denver 65 fair; Des Moines 75 cloudy; Indianapolis 80
hazy; Kansas City 71 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 77 partly cloudy;
Nashville 83 fair; New Orleans 77 fair; St. Louis 85 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 77 partly cloudy; Anchorage 63 partly cloudy;
Las Vegas 87 fair; Los Angeles 64 hazy; Phoenix 96 fair; Salt Lake
City 70 fair; San Diego 67 cloudy; San Francisco 58 fair; Seattle
57 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 64 partly cloudy; Toronto 73 cloudy.
</TEXT>
