<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0849EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Singapore-Released     07-16 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Singapore-Released,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Critic Released From Detention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today released a lawyer and
critic of the government who was detained in May after he met with
a U.S. diplomat, officials said.
   A statement released by the Home Affairs Ministry said Francis
Seow, a former solicitor general and ex-president of the country's
Law Society, was freed on condition that he not travel outside
Singapore or associate with foreign diplomats.
   Seow was detained May 6 under Singapore's Internal Security Act
after he met with U.S. diplomats including E. Mason Hendrickson,
then-first secretary of the U.S. Embassy's political section.
   The government expelled Hendrickson, saying he meddled in
Singapore's internal affairs by allegedly encouraging Seow and
other lawyers to contest the governing People's Action Party in the
next general election.
   Washington rejected the allegations, insisting Hendrickson's
actions were within accepted diplomatic bounds, and in turn ousted
a diplomat from Singapore.
   The Home Affairs Ministry statement said today that the order
releasing Seow would be ``revoked if Seow acts in any manner
prejudicial to the security of Singapore or breaches any
restrictive condition.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
