<DOCNO> AP880716-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0935EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-USRefugees     07-16 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-US Refugees,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Will Resume Processing Applications So Soviets Can Leave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy said today it will resume the
processing of thousands of Soviets seeking refugee status in
America but stranded in the Soviet Union because of a lack of State
Department funds.
   Many of the prospective refugees or their relatives in the
United States will now be asked to help pay their way to America,
the embassy said.
   The U.S. mission's action, announced in a statement, will begin
Monday. It follows criticism in Washington of the State
Department's decision to delay the emigration of Soviets granted
refugee status because of a surge in their numbers and a shortage
of money.
   That decision has left hundreds of Soviets in limbo. They had
sold their homes, quit their jobs and traveled to Moscow in the
expectation of receiving quick permission to leave for the United
States.
   On Friday, a group of 23 U.S. senators and nine House of
Representatives members called for revoking the suspension of
refugee processing begun July 1, which U.S. diplomats in Moscow say
has frozen the applications of about 3,400 people.
   In a letter, the senators told President Reagan: ``This decision
sends a terrible signal to those seeking freedom all over the
world, and could give the Soviets the opportunity to claim that it
is America and not the Soviet Union which is impeding emigration.''
   Last month, the embassy gave permission to a record 2,063
Soviets, 94 percent of them Armenians, to emigrate to the United
States. That was more than in all of fiscal year 1987, which ended
Sept. 30.
   U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock told reporters last week that
processing of the refugees was scheduled to resume on Oct. 1, the
beginning of the 1989 fiscal year, when more funds would become
available.
   But the Saturday statement said that starting Monday, ``the
embassy will interview immediately the approximately 400 applicants
who came to Moscow in the initial few days after July 1 so they can
proceed to Rome for entry processing to the U.S.''
   The mission said it would work with the other 3,000 Soviets ``to
seek every possible means to facilitate their timely departure for
the United States.''
</TEXT>
