<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     07-16 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Country's Top Executives to Meet on Nagorno-Karabakh Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tass reported Saturday that the executive
committee of the Soviet parliament will meet this week. It was
believed the topic of discussion would be the dispute involving
Nagorno-Karabakh, in the Azerbaijan republic.
   Armenians, who want to annex the region to their republic, have
been saying for weeks that they believed the Presidium of the
Supreme Soviet would meet Monday. The Tass dispatch was the first
official confirmation that, but the report didn't say what would be
discussed.
   The dispatch was from Stepanakert, the main city in
Nagorno-Karabakh.
   ``The situation in the Nagorno-Karbakh Autonomous Region is
becoming more tense with the approach of July 18, the day when a
meeting of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the U.S.S.R. is
to be held,'' the news agency reported.
   Armenians make up more than three-quarters of Nagorno-Karabakh's
160,000 residents. They have said the Presidium session will be
crucial to their decision on whether to continue a general strike
and street rallies pressing their demands for the region's
annexation.
   Tass said a general strike continued and food was in short
supply in Nagorno-Karabakh.
   The Delaware-sized region has been part of mostly Moslem
Azerbaijan since 1923. Armenians are mostly Christian.
   Last month, the Armenian parliament endorsed the annexation
demand, but Azerbaijani lawmakers refused to give their consent.
   The Nagorno-Karabakh legislature voted Tuesday to secede from
Azerbaijan and join Armenia, but the Azerbaijan parliament declared
the move illegal.
   Central Communist Party officials ruled out a transfer of
Nagorno-Karabakh in February, but the central government has not
reviewed the matter.
   The issue erupted in violence in February, when riots in the
Azerbaijani city of Sumgait killed 32 people, most of them
Armenians.
</TEXT>
