<2ND_LINE>AM-Widows' Rally,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Widows, Orphans, Lead March For Peace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANGELES, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Widows and orphans of assassination
victims led a solemn peace rally Saturday and appealed for an end
to the spate of killings that has gripped this city since May.
   About 1,000 women attended a Mass and joined a march in downtown
Angeles. After the march, they recited the rosary and offered a
``prayer for peace.''
   At least 38 people were killed in Angeles, home of the U.S.-run
Clark Air Base, in May and June. The city is 50 miles north of
Manila.
   Communist gunmen, who killed three Americans near the air base
last year, claimed responsibility for four of the recent killings
but attributed most to government forces and common criminals.
   Saturday's marchers held placards that pleaded for forgiveness
instead of revenge and ``Love, not hate.'' They clutched white
ribbons that organizers said symbolized peace.
   Widows took turns appealing for an end to the violence.
   Erlinda Cura, widow of human rights lawyer Ramos Cura who was
killed last month, said that while her husband's death was tragic,
``his blood will serve as a seed for us and his children to
continue fighting for his aspirations and principles.''
   Marina Tabliga, widow of slain army Sgt. Ric Tabliga, asked
assassins to spare other families, saying ``the suffering we widows
are experiencing is enough.''
</TEXT>
