<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis'Image     07-16 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis' Image,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegates See Dukakis as Dependable, Honest, Dull, Short</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats on the verge of nominating Michael
Dukakis for president see themselves picking a dependable but dull
fellow who has done well at his current job but lacks some
experience he would need for the new one.
   A handful of them suggest that the 5-foot-8-inch governor of
Massachusetts could use lifts in his shoes.
   Results of an Associated Press survey of delegates to the
Democratic National Convention found that while many give Dukakis
credit for his performance as governor, a roughly equal number are
concerned about his lack of experience in national and
international affairs.
   ``I suspect they (the Republicans) will make much of foreign
policy issues, but I've never seen an election decided by foreign
policy issues,'' said William Winpisinger, a delegate from Maryland
and president of the Machinists union.
   ``What happens at home is what counts, and he's got a good
record on that,'' Winpisinger said.
   More than 1,900 delegates _ about 46 percent of the 4,161 total
_ responded to the opinion survey and 583 gave Dukakis high marks
for his record and experience as governor, his skills as a manager
and his ability to deal with economic issues.
   However, 553 said he is weak in the areas of foreign policy,
national issues and in dealing with Congress.
   One hundred cited Dukakis for his honesty.
   ``And I think that's going to be a big issue in this campaign
... the Reagan administration sleaze factor,'' said Montana state
Rep. Dan Harrington, a Dukakis delegate. ``Dukakis has shown he's
above all that.''
   Asked to name Dukakis' strength, Elana Stampfer, an Oregon
delegate, replied: ``his managerial skills. Everyone thinks that's
boring, but I think it's exciting to have someone who will actually
be able to run government well.''
   ``Boring'' is one of the words that pops up repeatedly in
delegates' assessments of Dukakis.
   Of those responding to the survey, 288 said he was dull or
described his personality as cold, aloof, humorless or arrogant.
   ``How can I say this politely? The one weakness is he is
boring,'' said Gloria Johnson, a Jackson delegate from Maryland.
   ``He lulls his audiences to sleep,'' said Robert Williams, a
Jackson delegate from Oregon. ``You start out listening to him, but
by the middle of his speech, you've forgotten what he's said.''
   It also appears, according to the delegates, that being called a
liberal is more a curse than a compliment.
   Seventy-six classified the liberal label as a weakness, while
just three said it was a strength.
   On a more personal level: ``He's short,'' said Chris Fairchild,
a Dukakis delegate from Michigan. ``I really, honestly think that's
going to be trouble for him. How many presidents do you know that
were short?''
   Becoming a nominee for president of the United States may give
Dukakis a larger-than-life stature.
   ``When I saw him this week, he'd taken on an aura he didn't have
six months ago,'' said Sue Pate, a Dukakis delegate from Texas.
``So you didn't notice him being short.''
</TEXT>
