<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CampaignAbroad     07-16 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Abroad,0737</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campaign Abroad: Comment on Dukakis' Choice of Bentsen</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is some of what newspapers abroad had to say last week on
Gov. Michael Dukakis' choice of Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as his
Democratic running mate in the November presidential election:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CANADA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Montreal Gazette (independent): ``Mr. Dukakis' choice seems
astute, even though he now will have to bend over backward to make
sure Jesse Jackson and his supporters stay on board. Mr. Bentsen
brings quite a dowry to this marriage of convenience. He gives the
prospective Democratic ticket extensive experience in Washington,
something Mr. Dukakis lacks. He is a noted fund-raiser. He may help
Mr. Dukakis attract voters on the right. He brings geographical
balance to the Democratic ticket, and he will give ... George Bush,
who has Texan connections of his own, a fight for that important
state's votes.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The Globe and Mail of Toronto (national, independent): ``Mr.
Bentsen was the better choice for a winning ticket. He reassures
conservative Democrats and liberal Republicans that Mr. Dukakis ..
. is not an ideological liberal, and this large group of cross-over
voters is critical to Mr. Dukakis' prospects.
   ``Mr. Jackson is too volatile a personality to be that close to
the presidency, despite his admirable and potent campaign on the
progressive wing of the Democratic Party.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Financial Times (independent): ``Mr. Bentsen brings
indisputable qualifications, if no fire, to the ticket. Eighteen
years a senator, and, never forget, the man who defeated George
Bush to make it to the upper chamber, he has the Washington
experience Mr. Dukakis lacks. ...
   ``The real reason why the lot has fallen on Mr. Bentsen is
because of where he is from. Texas may be a law unto itself but it
is the third largest state of the union, the Democrats must carry
it and the formidable Bensen machine is likely to be more effective
with him on the ticket. ... His mere presence alongside Mr. Dukakis
is explicitly designed to tie Vice President George Bush, a
neo-Texan, down to a part of the country he thought he had in his
pocket and to a state which once rejected him, at the hands of a
man called Bentsen.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The Times of London (independent): ``Mr. Dukakis may be tainted
with Massachusetts liberalism, but Mr. Bentsen gives the appearance
of comfortable Southern conservatism.
   ``Mr. Dukakis is accused of haste and brashness; Mr. Bentsen, at
67, has the solid values of age. While Mr. Dukakis has no
experience of national political office, Mr. Bentsen is a skilled
manipulator of the levers of Washington power. Mr. Dukakis is
`ethnic'; Mr. Bentsen is patrician. ...
   ``It is clear that Mr. Dukakis intends to rely on his running
mate for delivering those Southern Democrats who voted for Mr.
Reagan. To that end his reassuring pro-defense and pro-business
attitudes will help. The fact that he is a self-made millionaire
(from insurance) will not hurt. He has always been a stout defender
of oil interests, and that will stand him in good stead in Oklahoma
and Louisiana, where the oil industry has been badly winded by the
price decline.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MEXICO</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Excelsior of Mexico City (independent): ``Why choose Bentsen?
In reality, it's a very lucid political maneuver. No candidate from
the Northeast can win a presidential election in the United States
without the support of two fundamental states: Texas and
California. Perhaps with this step by Dukakis, geopolitics might
become more favorable to the luck of the Democrats, or at least the
domination of Texas where Bush has an undeniable weight will be
disputed.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MALAYSIA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The New Straits Times of Kuala Lumpur (pro-government):
``Although a conservative, Senator Bentsen is credited with a
strong civil rights record. And although he may have ideological
differences with the main protagonist on the Democratic ticket, he
is said to be politically shrewd and competitive, and he commands a
strong political organization in Texas that can be brought to bear
in the South.
   ``In other words, he can still be an asset to Governor Dukakis
in the crucial presidential campaign.''
</TEXT>
