<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Court-AirBags 1stLd-Writethru a0416 07-16 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Court-Air Bags, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0416,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carmakers Can Delay Installing Passive Belts if Driver Has Air Bag</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf, Miller said, detailing bags
now being offered.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An auto safety group says it will decide
whether to appeal a court ruling that upholds a government decision
letting automakers put off until 1993 a requirement for passive
safety belts on a car's passenger side if the driver is protected
by an air bag.
   ``Essentially, what the court did is put passenger occupants (of
cars equipped with driver-side air bags) in a position of a
likelihood of harm when the driver will walk away from the crash,''
Joan Claybrook, head of Public Citizen, said Friday.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration had agreed to
a request by the Ford Motor Co., that allows continued use of
manual safety belts on the passenger side in cars that have
driver-side air bags.
   The highway safety agency in issuing the ruling last year agreed
with auto industry claims that more time was needed to develop air
bag systems for front-seat passengers.
   Public Citizen, a Washington-based public interest group,
claimed that the ruling postpones passive restraint protection for
car passengers for four years and puts them in additional danger.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals on Friday upheld the NHTSA decision,
throwing out Public Citizen's suit.
   Jeffrey Miller, deputy administrator of NHTSA, called the court
decision ``good news for consumers because air bags will now be
available sooner and in more cars.''
   Miller said the decision creates an incentive for automakers to
make driver-side air bags available while working on developing
systems that protect both drivers and front-seat passengers.
   Ford announced in June it will offer dual driver-passenger bags
on Lincoln Continentals being introduced this fall for the 1989
model year. Ford Tempo and Mercury Topaz models have offered
driver-only bags for several years.
   Chrylser Corp said in May it was including driver bags as
standard equipment in six models assembled after May 15 and would
have them on all models by 1990.
   Porsche offers driver-passenger bags on one model, and several
other foreign companies offer bags to protect the driver.
   An air bag is a device that inflates rapidly in an automobile
collision, protecting a driver's head and upper torso, before it
rapidly deflates.
   The Transportation Department several years ago directed
automakers to phase in passive restraints _ either air bags or
belts that automatically wrap around a person entering a car _ with
all cars to be equipped with the devices by the fall of 1989.
   Last year's ruling, which was upheld by the court Friday,
postponed the requirement in the case of front-seat passengers in
any car where the driver is protected by an air bag.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
