<DOCNO> AP880716-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 1153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen-Senate     07-16 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-Senate,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tower Sees a Democratic Stratagem in Bentsen's Dual Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Retransmitting a0523 to fix category code</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican John Tower, experienced at running
against a Democrat nominated simultaneously for the Senate and the
vice presidency, says Lloyd Bentsen's Texas campaign threatens to
become ``a bottomless pit people throw money in'' _ and a war chest
for the Democrats' national ticket.
   ``I think it's going to really be a tight rope for him (Bentsen)
to walk,'' says Tower, a former senator from Texas. ``It's going to
be pretty tricky business.''
   Tower, now an adviser to all-but-certain Republican presidential
nominee George Bush, says his camp has put lawyers to work on
sifting through campaign finance regulations.
   They will be quick to pounce on any violations of federal
election law that Bentsen makes as he mounts simultaneous campaigns
for vice president and re-election to the Senate, Tower said in an
interview Friday.
   Republicans worry that Bentsen's Senate campaign could become
``a bottomless pit people throw money in and use for the
presidential campaign,'' he said.
   Before being selected by Michael Dukakis as his running mate,
Bentsen had raised more than $5 million for his re-election bid _
more than any other senator.
   He got more money from political action committees than any
Senate candidate seeking election this year _ $1.46 million. By
contrast, Dukakis refuses to accept PAC funds.
   Tower had firsthand experience with a Texas law that allows a
candidate to campaign simultaneously for both offices _ as Bentsen
will do this fall.
   Tower ran against Lyndon B. Johnson for the Senate in 1960.
Johnson was also running as the Democratic nominee for vice
president with John F. Kennedy.
   Johnson won both races and gave up his Senate seat for the vice
presidency. A special election was called and Tower won.
   Although Johnson juggled both campaigns in 1960, Tower says
Bentsen faces some knotty problems because of stricter federal
election spending laws.
   Says one Republican operative: ``It's a mine field he has to
walk through. ... Anytime someone plows new ground you're bound to
dig up a bone.''
   Counters Bentsen: ``They tell me it's been done before in
Texas.''
   Jim Boynton, assistant executive director of the Texas
Democratic Party, said Bentsen is ``one of the most organized
candidates you'll ever run across'' and will now just ``put another
step of organization in place.''
   He said Republican vigilance of Bentsen's finances is prompted
because they ``have to have some way to challenge the senator.''
   Under Texas law, if Bentsen were to abandon his Senate race, the
Democrats could not name a replacement candidate and the seat
automatically would fall into Republican hands.
   It would go to his Republican challenger, Rep. Beau Boulter, a
two-term congressman from Amarillo who complains that Bentsen's
dual candidacies are unfair and unethical.
   Tower sees other problems for Bentsen. Some of the same people
who support Bentsen for Senate also support Bush and Republican
Gov. Bill Clements. Tower calls them ``pragmatic business types.''
   Moreover, Tower said, things have changed since he ran against
Lyndon Johnson.
   ``Taking comfort in the 1960 analogy is taking comfort in a weak
reed indeed,'' he said.
   Texas Republicans in 1960 were barely worthy of the GOP name,
but today they hold the office of governor, a seat in the Senate,
10 in the House and dozens of posts in the legislature and control
the courthouses in the state's two largest counties _ Dallas and
Harris, Tower said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
