<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Violence     07-16 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Violence,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Suspected Guerrillas Killed In Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers killed two men
believed to be African National Congress guerrillas in a national
park near the Mozambique border, the military said Saturday.
   Spokesman Ian Buck said the men were killed in a remote area of
Kruger National Park on Friday. The shooting occurred near the spot
where two alleged ANC guerrillas were killed in a similar incident
Thursday.
   The ANC is the main black guerrilla group fighting to overthrow
South Africa's white-led government.
   Buck said two suspects escaped into Mozambique in Friday's
confrontation. He said the military suffered no casualties in the
joint army-air force operation in Kruger, South Africa's largest
national park.
   On Saturday, three black men were killed in two separate
attacks, police said in their daily unrest report. The report
covers incidents from the preceding 24 hours.
   Two men were killed and five were injured in black factional
fighting in a township outside the southeastern city of
Pietermaritzburg, police said.
   A bystander was killed when an assailant fired on a security
force vehicle in a township outside Cape Town, police said.
Security forces arrested one man, police said.
</TEXT>
