<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Theme Bjt   07-16 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Theme, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Will Leave the Convention to Campaign Among Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis intends to use the Democratic
nominating convention to launch his presidential campaign with a
call to end the ``borrow and spend'' prosperity of the Reagan years
that he says masks great uneasiness across America about the future.
   After flying to the convention in Atlanta on Sunday with his
designated running mate, Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, Dukakis will use
the four-day celebration of his candidacy to dramatize his economic
theme by going beyond the customary convention appearances to
campaign among local residents _ at a factory gate and elsewhere.
   ``That will be the central issue of this campaign, an economic
future that creates good jobs in every part of this country,''
Dukakis said in a pre-convention interview in the governor's office
of the Massachusetts Statehouse.
   After the convention, Dukakis and Bentsen will leave Atlanta
together for what campaign manager Susan Estrich said would be a
coast-to-coast campaign trip with a first stop in Texas.
   That inaugural trip by the new Democratic ticket will include
``a good many rallies, built on the excitement which we think is
going to come out of the convention.''
   Dukakis was spending the hours before his departure trying to
deal with a state budget deficit that offered Republicans an
opportunity to challenge his image as a tough manager who has
balanced state budgets while holding the line on taxes.
   The picture of the nation's economy offered by Dukakis will
contrast sharply with the view put forth by Vice President George
Bush, his certain Republican opponent.
   Republicans cite an unemployment rate that is half what it was
in December 1982 and inflation and interest figures far below what
they were in the final year of the presidency of Democrat Jimmy
Carter.
   ``We can build on the stable, record-setting economic pace of
the Reagan-Bush years, we can continue to pursue peace through
strength, or we can head down a road already traveled,'' said
Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas after leading a GOP
delegation to the Democrats' convention city.
   Despite the improving economic statistics, Republican pollster
Richard Wirthlin has said that since December 1986, his monthly
surveys have found a majority of Americans saying the country was
headed in the wrong direction.
   ``There is great uncertainty out there,'' Dukakis said. ``Why
the great uncertainty?
   ``The American people know you can't build a strong economic
future on a credit card. You can't borrow and spend, borrow and
spend, and borrow and spend your way to prosperity.''
   As for the improving economic statistics, Dukakis said, ``Those
numbers, averages mask all kinds of problems.''
   Bentsen refers to a ``Swiss Cheese economy'' in which the
general prosperity is pocked by bad times.
   ``Thirty-two percent unemployment in Starr County, Texas,'' was
an example cited by Dukakis.
   He also blamed Reagan administration antitrust policy for
tolerating ``takeover artists circling all sorts of healthy
companies all over this country. As soon as they make an
acquisition, 600 or 700 people are out in the street, or more. ...
Over a trillion dollars worth of debt which our kids and grandkids
are going to have to pay is no way to run a railroad.''
   Estrich described the convention as ``a time when the
opportunities to communicate through the media are enormous, so
we'll be spending plenty of time trying to take advantage of those
opportunities because in Mike Dukakis we have a candidate who has
just burst onto the national scene.''
   For the first time, say Dukakis aides, the Democrats are
recruiting top talent from the world of commercial advertising to
work with political media experts _ a practice common in GOP
campaigns for years.
   One of the people recruited to help Dukakis is Ed McCabe who was
responsible for the Frank Perdue slogan, ``It takes a tough man to
make a tender chicken.''
</TEXT>
