<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0506 07-16 0922</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0506,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Forces Pick Up VP Forms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 12 grafs with Jackson VP petitions, McCurry
comments, picking up in 5th graf pvs, For his; trims from end;
^By TERENCE HUNT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson talked about smoothing over
their pre-convention quarrels, but Jackson's forces picked up
nominating petitions that could be used to challenge the selection
of Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen for the No. 2 spot on the Democratic
presidential ticket.
   As Jackson's ``Rainbow Express'' bus caravan rolled toward
Atlanta, it remained anyone's guess whether his supporters would
attempt to disrupt the convention or fall in behind the
Dukakis-Bentsen slate.
   Publicly, Jackson and Dukakis edged away from a confrontation in
Atlanta, with Jackson saying he harbored ``no acrimony or
hostility'' toward the Massachusetts governor.
   However, Jackson campaign representatives picked up the
nominating papers both for president, the position he lost to
Dukakis, and for vice president, the job he wanted as a consolation
prize. Jackson said he would not put his name in nomination for the
vice presidency but left open the possibility that someone else
might.
   ``I'm not putting my name into nomination, but if it were to
happen it certainly is an option that would be within the rules of
the convention. It would not be breaking precedent,'' Jackson said
on ABC's ``Nightline.''
   Dukakis, the certain Democratic presidential nominee, said he
wants Jackson to be a player in party affairs. ``I want him
involved, I want his staff people involved,'' the Massachusetts
governor said in Boston.
   The wrangling between Dukakis and Jackson remained solidly at
center stage just two days before the opening of the party meeting
at the Omni center.
   Putting the best face on developments, Mike McCurry, the
spokesman for the Democratic National Committee, said,
``Negotiations between the two campaigns are going very, very well
and that gives us all a great deal of optimism as we prepare for
the start of our convention.''
   He said Paul Kirk, the party's chairman, ``has been involved in
these discussions and asked me to assure all of you things are
going swimmingly.'' He declined to say what was being discussed,
but said actual negotiations over platform differences have not
resumed.
   As Jackson's bus caravan headed toward a welcoming ceremony in
Atlanta this afternoon, Dukakis went to his Statehouse office in
Boston, arriving at 8:30 a.m. to oversee the Legislature's final
work on a fiscal 1989 budget.
   ``We're going to wrap things up,'' Dukakis said, and two hours
later, the Legislature did just that, completing a marathon
23{-hour session.
   Dukakis planned to study the $11.75 billion budget and sign it
in a ceremony Sunday before leaving for the convention. Democratic
and Republican lawmakers said he would have to veto at least $150
million in the package to bring the state's budget into balance.
   For his part, Jackson, the runner-up in the primaries, said his
supporters must be integrated into the party structure.
   ``It means our constituency must be involved in the Democratic
National Committee and in state committees. It means defining roles
for those constituents in the campaign,'' Jackson said. ``If I am
to have responsibility in that campaign, I must have a role
commensurate with that responsibility.''
   Dukakis and Jackson agreed to have their top aides meet in
Atlanta tonight to discuss differences.
   Meanwhile, former President Jimmy Carter toured the convention
center today, surrounded by the noise of hammering and sawing as
workmen put finishing touches on camera platforms and a railing in
front of the speaker's platform.
   Carter played down the likelihood of convention friction
generated by Jackson.
   ``I think he will be adequately included,'' Carter said. ``The
inevitability is that they will work out any differences. We'll
come out of here with a united party.''
   ``I think the conversations yesterday between Dukakis and
Jackson and their staffs show that the problems are being worked
out,'' Carter said.
   While Jackson arrives in Atlanta later today, Dukakis has put
off his arrival until Sunday, the eve of the convention's opening.
Dukakis planned a quick stop in Washington Sunday afternoon to pick
up Bentsen, a senator from Texas, before the two headed on to
Atlanta.
   George Bush, certain to win the Republican nomination to face
Dukakis in the general election, was heading to Wyoming today for a
4{-day fishing trip with his pal and political mentor, James A.
Baker III, who is expected to give up his job as Treasury secretary
to run the Bush campaign.
   Bush does not plan to let the Democrats have the limelight
exclusively next week. The vice president will come out of
seclusion Wednesday and hit the campaign trail, competing for
attention on the final two days of the Democratic convention.
   Differences between Jackson and Dukakis have dominated the
Democrats' pre-convention picture since Dukakis announced Tuesday
that Bentsen would be his running mate. Jackson and his supporters
were infuriated that they learned of Bentsen's selection from
reporters and not from Dukakis.
   However, with the convention fast approaching, the words of
anger were losing their edge on Friday.
   ``We simply cannot win without each other,'' Jackson said at a
news conference in Louisville, Ky. ``We can only win with each
other. It is in our distinct advantage to find common ground.''
   Jckson, whose staff had broken off negotiations with Dukakis'
aides, called the governor on the telephone, saying later the two
have no ``acrimony and hostility'' but only policy matters to
resolve.
   ``I see the tension we're going through as normal and healthy,''
Jackson said.
</TEXT>
