<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Convention-Bedlam     07-16 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention-Bedlam,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Bad Omen in the Omni</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was just one man touring the hall Saturday
where 11,000 will gather for the Democratic National Convention,
but the crush of press squeezing through the small passageways in
the arena was a bad omen for next week.
   ``Don't push!'', ``Get out of the way!'' and other less
printable exclamations echoed across the floor of the Omni on
Saturday as former President Jimmy Carter was trailed by about 40
reporters and camera operators.
   Dan Lee, assistant executive officer of the convention, took the
Georgia native on a tour of the facility that will host the first
national convention in his home state.
   Carter strolled across the convention floor, where delegate
seats are so tightly packed together that some people had to turn
sideways to walk between the rows. Talking to reporters as he went,
Carter stood at the podium where he will speak on Monday night. A
wire rope ladder reaching to the ceiling dangled behind him.
   The former president, who spends some time now working on
refurbishing homes for poor Americans, talked with the carpenters
who are hammering together a last-minute addition to the podium, a
low walkway just off the floor.
   Rosalynn Carter choose to stay away from the crush from the
start.
   As the tour of the floor ended, the former president looked
around and said, ``Has anybody seen my wife?''
</TEXT>
