<DOCNO> AP880716-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 1228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis'Successor     07-16 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis' Successor,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Potential Mass. Gubernatorial Candidates at the Convention</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Democratic Convention Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic National Convention could provide
a golden opportunity for Massachusetts Democrats interested in
succeeding Michael Dukakis as governor.
   Without doubt, ``politicians will be politicking at a
convention,'' Rep. Chester G. Atkins, chairman of the state party
and head of the state's convention delegation, said when asked if
there would be gubernatorial maneuvering this week.
   If Dukakis wins the presidency, Lt. Gov. Evelyn Murphy would
take over and would be running as the incumbent in the next regular
election, in 1990. Dukakis hasn't said whether he would seek a new
term that year if he should lose the presidential race.
   Atkins said lobbying this week will be ``very, very subtle.''
   ``I think you'll see quiet diplomacy,'' said the two-term
congressman, who until recently was himself considering running for
governor to replace Dukakis. ``People first and foremost want to do
what they can to get Dukakis elected.''
   ``Secondly, this is a very, very sophisticated audience you're
dealing with. They're not unaware of all the rituals of political
courtship. And anybody who goes into the courtship ritual outside
of the mating season'' won't be well received, Atkins said in a
pre-convention interview last week.
   The most-mentioned Democrats for the office will all be here for
the convention.
   Lt. Gov. Murphy and Boston Mayor Raymond Flynn are both
delegates. Attorney General James Shannon is here as a member of
the Rules Committee. Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II, son of the late
Sen. Robert F. Kennedy, has no official convention role, but he
will be in town for an event with Martin Luther King III.
   Early polls show Murphy, Kennedy and Flynn close to each other,
with Shannon and Atkins in single digits. Atkins ruled out a
gubernatorial run last month, in part to show House leaders he was
serious about wanting an open seat on the House Appropriations
Committee. Kennedy, a freshman, is fighting for the same seat.
</TEXT>
