<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Burnett-NTSB     07-16 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burnett-NTSB,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transportation Board Chairman May Be Victim of Presidential
Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The renomination of Jim Burnett as chairman of
the National Transportation Safety Board has bogged down in the
Senate in what Burnett's supporters say is an effort to replace him
with a Democrat after the presidential elections.
   Burnett, an outspoken former Arkansas judge, was renominated by
President Reagan last April 19 for a fourth term as chairman of the
NTSB, which investigates airline accidents and other aviation
safety issues.
   But the Senate Commerce Committee has yet to schedule a hearing
on the nomination and Burnett's current two-year term ends August
13. Should he not win Senate confirmation by then, the board's vice
chairman automatically assumes the chairmanship temporarily.
   ``There's nothing scheduled (on the Burnett case) at least in
the next few weeks,'' said Emelio Pardo, a spokesman for the
Commerce Committee. He said the full committee is waiting for its
aviation subcommittee to make its views known on the nomination.
   But committee sources say that relations between Burnett and
Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., the chairman of the aviation
subcommittee, have soured in recent months. Burnett publicly
opposed legislation pushed by Ford that calls for the Federal
Aviation Administration to be made independent of the
Transportation Department.
   ``He is not in Burnett's corner and he's not alone,'' said Jim
Fleming administrative assistant to Ford when asked about the
Kentucky senator's views of Burnett.
   Fleming said consideration of presidential nominations is a
matter for the full committee and not a subcommittee.
   If the Senate does not act on Burnett and Michael Dukakis wins
the presidential election in November, a Democrat likely would be
nominated for the post.
   Ironically, many Democratic members of the Senate Commerce
Committee came to Burnett's aid two years ago when his renomination
by the Reagan administration for a time was put into doubt because
of reported opposition from Elizabeth Dole, who was then
transportation secretary.
   In May 1986, the White House allowed Burnett's tenure as
chairman to run out and did not renominate him until July after
pressure from some members of Congress, including some of the
senators who now are cool toward his renomination.
   If not confirmed as chairman, Burnett is likely to remain on the
board at least until the November election. He was active in
Arkansas Republican Party politics and worked in several George
Bush campaigns. Should Bush win the election, he likely would
renominate Burnett next year.
   Burnett, 40, has been a member of the NTSB since 1981. He often
has won praise from Congress for his frank assessments of aviation
safety and criticism of the FAA's ability to monitor air traffic
growth and the airlines.
   In the spring of 1987, Burnett attracted widespread attention by
suggesting that the FAA was allowing air traffic growth to exceed
the capabilities of air traffic controllers. He suggested the
number of commercial flights in some section of the country be
curtailed.
   Before coming to Washington in 1981, Burnett was a judge in Van
Buren and Damascus, Ark., and a special associate justice of the
Arkansas Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
