<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-Democrats 1stLd-Writethru   07-16 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Democrats, 1st Ld-Writethru,390</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Reagan Attacks Demriter</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, using his weekly radio
speech for a blast at the Democratic economic record, charged today
that party leaders gathering for their convention in Atlanta ``want
to take America back to the failed policies of the past.''
   Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa, speaking in response for the Democrats,
said it's in economic matters where the Reagan administration has
left the country weakest.
   Reagan said, ``Before we came to Washington, our economy was in
a mess.'' He said his administration has produced the longest
period of peacetime economic growth in American history.
   ``We cut tax rates, pared back regulations, limited the growth
of government spending, and we did all this to get government out
of the way so that individuals and enterprises had incentives to
grow, to invest, to innovate, to create jobs,'' the president said.
   ``It's ironic,'' Reagan said, ``that just as countries around
the world are adopting the same pro-growth policies our
administration put in place, so many in the Democratic Party want
to go in the opposite direction.''
   ``Today, we face an historic opportunity, a chance to remove the
fear of the boom and bust cycle once and for all, replacing it with
consistent low-tax, limited-government policies,'' he said.
   Reagan said he believed many rank-and-file Democrats would
support this, but added, ``Sadly the leaders in charge of the
convention will want to take America back to the failed policies of
the past.''
   The president urged his listeners, as they watch the Democratic
convention on television next week, to ask: ``Is the Democratic
party, is its nominee for president going to keep taxes low and
government growth under control, or are they going to go back to
the very policies that could wreck our economy again?''
   Harkin, in his radio response, said Democrats in Atlanta will be
sending out the message: ``Let's repair the damage and bring
integrity and competence back to government.''
   ``Today the greatest threat to our national security is not
military _ it's economic. Yet, that's where this administration has
left us the weakest,'' Harkin said.
   He accused Reagan of setting the ship of state adrift and also
criticized Vice President George Bush for avoiding responsibility.
   ``The captain's been asleep at the wheel, and his first mate
doesn't seem to ever be on deck when decisions are made,'' Harkin
said.
</TEXT>
