<HEAD>Pilot Who Testified Against Lehder Sentenced To Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot who testified against
convicted cocaine kingpin Carlos Lehder Rivas was sentenced to
seven years in prison despite his help in that and three other
investigations.
   Andrew Richard Barnes, 32, a British subject who lives in
Spinnerstown, Pa., was described by prosecutors as important in
obtaining Lehder's conviction, and instrumental in helping
investigate a heroin ring, a Philadelphia organized crime family
and allegedly corrupt Bahamian officials. Barnes was sentenced
Thursday.
   He testified in March and April that he smuggled 3 tons of
cocaine for Lehder from Colombia to the Bahamas, and from the
Bahamas to the United States, in 1978 and 1980. He said he flew an
additional 14 loads of marijuana and one of cocaine for others
after breaking with Lehder.
   Barnes pleaded guilty in a secret court proceeding during
Lehder's seven-month trial.
