<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-SouthAfrica     07-16 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-South Africa,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade With South Africa May Be Leveling Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese trade with South Africa appears to be
leveling off, relieving some of Japan's embarrassment at having
become its largest trading partner.
   Before 1987, the United States did the most business with South
Africa, which has been condemned internationally for the apartheid
race policy that preserves power for the 5 million whites and
denies the 26 million blacks a voice in national affairs.
   Finance Ministry figures released Tuesday showed two-way trade
was down for the second consecutive month because of a sharp
decline in imports, but exports to South Africa remained strong.
   As other countries imposed sanctions on South Africa to protest
apartheid and saw their trade figures shrink, Japan let its
companies fill the gap and has been criticized for doing so.
   Some Japanese newspapers said trade was not really declining,
but Foreign Ministry spokesman Yoshifumi Matsuda told reporters
Thursday they should concentrate on yen-based trade figures rather
than those expressed in dollars.
   In dollars, two-way trade was up 13.3 percent to $2.2 billion
for the first six months of 1988, compared with the same 1987
period, but in yen the value dropped 3 percent to 272 billion, with
the decline starting in April.
   ``We do expect that the new trend after April will continue as
such,'' Matsuda said.
   Japan also renewed its call on South Africa to release Nelson
Mandela, the imprisoned leader of the African National Congress,
Matsuda announced.
   In addition, he said Japan has gone beyond most Western
countries in breaking diplomatic ties with South Africa and
prohibiting direct investment.
   Japan's bilateral trade with South Africa also has declined for
the past two months when expressed in dollars. The $325 million of
trade in June was 14.5 percent below June 1987, the Finance
Ministry reported. The decline was largely attributed to imports,
which plunged 26.6 percent to $158.1 million in June from a year
ago.
   Exports continued growing, though not as rapidly as six months
ago. In June, Japan exported $166.9 million worth of goods to South
Africa, 1.4 percent more than a year ago. But for the first six
months of this year, exports soared 45.3 percent to $1.14 billion,
according to the Finance Ministry's customs clearance statistics.
   In 1987, Japan's trade with South Africa totaled $4.27 billion,
a 19 percent increase from the previous year that proved
embarrassing.
   Foreign Minister Susuke Uno asked Japanese business leaders
early this year to reduce the trade and suggested the Ministry of
International Trade and Industry coordinate a guideline for
Japanese companies to follow.
   The powerful Federation of Economic Organizations, known as
Keidanren, which consists of some 1,000 major Japanese
corporations, said the Keidanren is not in a position to control
its members' business activities.
   Analysts attributed the recent decline in imports to decisions
by several supermarket chains and department stores to stop selling
South African products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
