<HEAD>U.S. Lawyer Wants Oil Rig Cases Heard in Texas Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American lawyer said Friday he will
try to have lawsuits involving the Piper Alpha oil platform
explosion and fire heard in a Texas court.
   Benton Musslewhite of Houston told a news conference in Aberdeen
total settlements in the world's worst oilfield disaster could
reach $1 billion.
   He did not say whether he he would handle cases for relatives of
the 166 men killed when the North Sea oil rig was engulfed by
flames July 6.
   The platform, with 230 men aboard, was operated by the Los
Angeles-based Occidental Petroleum Corp.
   Musslewhite said damages against oil companies need to be
punitive so the companies will say ``we can't afford not to be safe
or we will be put out of business.''
   Workers from Texas troubleshooter Paul ``Red'' Adair's
organization continued efforts to cap five of the platform's 36
wellheads that still were burning, Occidental said in a statement.
   It said work to clear debris from the tilting platform continues
when weather permits and drilling of a relief shaft has begun.
   Occidental said one more body was recovered from the sea,
bringing to the number found to 26. Ten survivors remained in
hospitals, the statement said.
