<2ND_LINE>AM-Mrs Letterman,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Found Incompetent To Stand Trial Second Time In Letterman
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who claimed to be talk show host
David Letterman's wife Friday was found incompetent a second time
to stand trial on charges she broke into the comedian's home and
stole his car.
   Norwalk Superior Court Judge James Bingham ordered Margaret Ray,
36, to undergo six months of psychiatric treatment in the state
hospital, where she has been a patient for the past several weeks.
   New Canaan police allege Ray broke into Letterman's home and
lived there for several days in May before stealing his car.
   Authorities became suspicious and arrested Ray when she and her
3-year-old son drove up to a Lincoln Tunnel toll booth in
Letterman's Porsche but couldn't pay the $3 toll. She told police
she was Letterman's wife and the boy was their son.
   Letterman asked police to drop the charges and she was released
from a Hudson County, N.J., jail three days later.
   Ray allegedly returned to Letterman's house that day, and police
said they found her eating canned pineapple and writing what she
said were scripts for Letterman's show.
   The charges were reinstated and Ray faces two counts of
second-degree burglary and one count of first-degree larceny.
   The judge ruled last month that Ray wasn't competent to stand
trial because she could understand the charges but was unable to
assist in her defense.
   Friday's hearing was granted to allow time for another
psychiatric examination of Ray, who objected to a first report that
described her as delusional.
   Psychiatrist Sander H. Fogle told the judge Friday he believed
Ray couldn't assist an attorney in defending herself against the
charges.
   The judge scheduled another hearing Oct. 14 to reconsider his
competency finding.
   Ray is being held and treated at the Fairfield Hills Hospital.
</TEXT>
