<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Africa-Summit     07-16 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Africa-Summit,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southern African leaders say apartheid doomed to fail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of nine black-ruled nations in
southern Africa ended a conference Friday with a call on South
Africa to concede that its policy of apartheid ``is doomed to
failure.''
   The one-day meeting was held to determine ways for the nine
countries to reduce their economic dependence on South Africa.
   Quett Masire, president of Botswana and chairman of the South
African Development Coordination Conference, said in the keynote
address: ``The promise of political independence is progressively
turning into a nightmare.''
   He said the high population growth in the area was causing
unemployment and preventing economic gains by the conference
members _ Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique, Swaziland,
Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
   Two other speakers, President Joaquim Chissano of Mozambique and
Prime Minister Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, accused South Africa of
trying to undermine its neighbors and hamper their quest for
economic self-reliance.
   ``Lasting peace will continue to elude our region until
apartheid comes to an end in South Africa,'' Mugabe said. He urged
the black-ruled nations to continue upgrading ports, highways and
rail lines to reduce the volume of traffic going through South
Africa.
   Under South Africa's laws and customs, apartheid establishes a
racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no
vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy
and maintain separate residential districts, schools and health
services.
   Oliver Tambo, president of the African National Congress, was
among several ANC officials attending the meeting. The ANC is the
main guerrilla movement fighting white domination in South Africa.
   Masire spoke of South African ``terrorist activities'' but his
speech dealt primarily with economic issues.
   The international trade system ``exposes us to
ever-deteriorating terms of trade and makes us the perennial
objects of charity,'' he said, and unless the system changes ``our
existence as self-respecting nations is in serious jeopardy.''
   He appealed for increased coordination of economic policies and
a strengthening of regional trade ties.
   Others attending the conference were presidents Kenneth Kaunda
of Zambia and Ali Hassan Mwini of Tanzania and Prime Minister Sotja
Dlamini of Swaziland. Angola, Malawi and Lesotho were represented
by Cabinet ministers.
   ANC spokesman Thabo Mbeki said in Maputo his organization was
concernd about bombings of civilian targets in South Africa and
some of the 29 bombs that have exploded in public places this year
may be ``deliberate enemy provocation.''
   South African police have blamed the ANC for the bombings.
   ``We ourselves are puzzled about these bombs which seem to be
directed against civilians,'' Mbeki told the Mozambican national
news agency AIM.
   He said civilians will be hurt in the growing conflict but
``none of our units operating inside the country have reported
having been involved in any of these operations.''
   Mbeki said the ANC policy of striking at army and police
installations has not changed, and does not include attacking
civilians ``be they black or white.''
   Police blame the bombings for 15 deaths and say 112 people have
been wounded. Six black civilians and three white civilians were
killed, two mixed-race babies perished when their mother gave birth
prematurely and four black men died when explosives they were
carrying blew up, according to police.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
