<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IMF-Malawi     07-16 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IMF-Malawi,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Malawi Gets First Easy Loan from International Monetary Fund</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Malawi, a small and poor republic in
southeastern Africa, will get the first easy loan under a new plan
set up by the International Monetary Fund, it was announced Friday.
   Malawi will pay interest of just 0.5 percent a year on the $72.5
million loan and can use the proceeds to buy foreign goods and to
help pay old debts.
   The country's 7.4 million people earned an average of $160 each
in 1986, the last year for which estimates were available. Since
1965, income had been growing at a rate of just 1.5 percent a year
and life expectancy was 45 years.
   Malawi already owes the fund the equivalent of $99 million out
of a total debt that had reached $1.1 billion in 1986. It will have
5{ years before it needs to start paying back the new loan, with
repayment to be completed within 15{ years.
   It is the first loan from what the fund calls its Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility, intended to help the poorest
countries, especially those in Africa. The borrowing government
must promise to make some basic changes in its policies in order to
get the loan.
   Malawi is promising to cut its government deficit and the
deficit of government-owned industries in an effort to curb
inflation. It also is trying to promote private business.
</TEXT>
