<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PilotFound     07-16 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pilot Found,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Stranded In Lake Michigan Rescued After 26 Hours</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH HAVEN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot who was stranded in Lake
Michigan 26 hours emerged from his ordeal Friday with little more
than hunger pangs and a headache.
   Michael J. Edison, 43, of St. Paul, Minn., was spotted about 8
a.m. inside his floating single-engine Cessna 206 by the crew of
The Steelhead, a Michigan Department of Natural Resources research
boat.
   ``He said he'd been there about 24 hours, so he was mighty happy
to see us,'' said Dave Johnson, a DNR district fish biologist.
   The plane, which was equipped with pontoons, was about seven
miles northwest of South Haven and about two miles offshore, U.S.
Coast Guard officials said. The plane sustained only minor damage.
   When the aircraft hit the lake, a life raft apparently hit
Edison from behind and he lost consciousness for most of the night,
Johnson said.
   He declined medical attention, and was in good condition except
for a bump on his head, Coast Guard officials said.
   Edison, an insurance executive and experienced pilot, was flying
from Grand Rapids to St. Paul when air traffic controllers in
Minneapolis lost radar contact with the plane at 5:50 a.m. EDT
Thursday. Just before the plane disappeared from radar, Edison
reported oil pressure trouble.
   ``He was getting low on oil pressure and then did something to
the throttle and the engine surged,'' said Mort Edelstein,
spokesman for the Federal Aviation Administration in Chicago.
   ``He decided to make a water landing but did not radio his
position. The waves were high and the nose tucked under the
water,'' Edelstein said. Coast Guard officials estimated waves at 2
feet to 3 feet.
   After regaining consciousness, Edison tried to lie down because
he felt sick and accidentally tore out radio wires with his knee,
Edelstein said.
   ``To top it all off, he didn't have a wristwatch so he didn't
know what time it was,'' Edelstein said. Edison also didn't have
any food.
   At dawn, Edison fired up the plane and tried to taxi to shore,
which was in sight, Edelstein said. ``At that moment, he saw the
DNR boat and they towed him in.''
   After his plane was towed to the Coast Guard station at South
Haven, with Edison steering it, he spoke with FAA officials by
telephone. He declined to speak with media.
   ``We know this is a miracle,'' Edison's wife, Bonnie, told the
St. Paul Pioneer Dispatch after hearing that her husband was safe.
``There were hundreds of people praying for him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
