<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Sniper     07-16 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Sniper,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Kill Rooftop Sniper in Jerusalem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-terrorist squad shot and killed a
mentally disturbed man Friday after he wounded one person and
sprayed gunfire from a rooftop, police said.
   Two police officers were later attacked and injured by the
sniper's relatives, who were enraged by the killing, Israel army
radio said.
   A witness, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the sniper
was killed after a brief gun battle with police.
   Authorities said the sniper was shot at a staircase of the
two-story home when he pointed his loaded M-16 assault rifle at the
police, authorities said.
   Israel army radio identified the sniper as Motti Aharon.
   It quoted family members as saying they had persuaded Aharon to
come down after they rushed to the scene. The report said family
members, angered by the killing, hurled stones at reporters and
attacked police officers, injuring two. It gave no details of their
injuries.
   Jerusalem police spokesman Rafi Levy told reporters at the scene
that the five-hour crisis started when the assailant, a 34-year-old
man armed with an M-16 and two magazines of ammunition, barricaded
himself on the roof of the home.
   He said residents of the house, in a poor Jewish neighborhood
known as Katamon-G, were evacuated.
   Dozens of police and emergency medical vehicles sealed off the
area, and police sharpshooters took positions on surrounding
rooftops.
   Police psychologists were also called in to try to negotiate
with the sniper, who demanded a helicoper, food, and cigarettes.
   Levy said the sniper had a history of mental disturbances and
was ``known to the police, but not as a criminal.''
   He said the man, who is divorced, had ended contacts with his
family two years ago but went to the house Friday to visit his
father.
   He said the sniper apparently obtained his weapon in the army,
where he was doing reserve service.
   Witnesses said the man fired several rounds of automatic fire.
   Levy said the gunman fired a round in the building's courtyard
and wounded a 50-year-old neighbor. The injured man, who was not
identified, told reporters the sniper ``demanded money and then
started shooting.''
   One witness told The Associated Press he saw the sniper
``dressed in a khaki T-shirt and running around on the roof like a
madman.''
   Mayor Teddy Kollek, who also went to the scene, said before the
killing that he felt sorry for the assailant. ``A poor man, a
psychopath, and look what's happening: fire brigade, police,
ambulances,'' he said.
   Police tried to persuade the man to come down. They later held
negotiations from a neighboring building.
</TEXT>
