<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-SovietTrade     07-16 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Soviet Trade,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese-Soviet Trade Up by Almost a Third</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese-Soviet trade rose by nearly a third in
the first half of this year over the same period last year, an
official report said Friday. The increase reflected improving
relations between the two communist countries.
   The Xinhua News Agency said China sold the Soviets $670 million
worth of goods and imported $627 million worth from January to June
in the largely barter trade.
   It said the two-way trade was up 32 percent over January-June
1987. The agency predicted continued growth.
   China has refused to normalize political relations with Moscow,
which have been chilly since an ideological split in the 1960s.
China says the Soviets must first reduce their troop presence at
the border and persuade Vietnam to withdraw its soldiers from
Cambodia.
   However, the two countries have steadily increased cultural,
trade and other non-political exchanges during the 1980s.
   Xinhua said the Soviets largely buy agricultural products and
raw materials from China, including corn, soybeans and meat.
   Mechanical products, from refrigerators to locomotives, make up
30 percent of China's purchases from the Soviet Union, with the
rest of the purchases consisting of timber, steel, fertilizer and
raw materials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
