<DOCNO> AP880716-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zambia-Elections     07-16 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zambia-Elections,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kaunda Picked as Sole Candidate in Zambian Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's ruling party picked longtime
President Kenneth Kaunda on Friday as its only candidate for
presidential elections this year.
   The influential southern African leader has come under
increasing criticism this year for his handling of the nation's
deepening economic crisis. Zambia, like many countries on the
continent, is plagued by heavy foreign debt and severe poverty.
   However, Kaunda will stand unopposed for a sixth four-year term
as leader of the country and of the ruling United National
Independence Party, its secretary-general, Grey Zulu, said at a
news conference in the capital.
   Zulu said 6,000 party officials from around Zambia will convene
in Kabwe, 70 miles north of the capital, from Aug. 18-23 to vote on
Kaunda for party president.
   After election as party president, Kaunda is required by the
constitution to win a majority of at least two thirds of the votes
cast in subsequent national presidential elections. The later
elections are not yet scheduled.
   Since 1964, Kaunda has been challenged once for the presidency.
In 1973, he was opposed by veteran politicians Harry Nkumbula and
Simon Kapwepwe, whose campaigns foundered when party officials
elected Kaunda by general acclamation.
</TEXT>
