<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Newborn-Airliner     07-16 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newborn-Airliner,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents Visit Abandoned Baby; Father To Request Immediate Custody</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a baby girl left at birth in
the restroom of an airliner visited the hospitalized infant Friday,
and the father promised to fight for custody.
   Christina Marie Locasto, charged with abandoning the infant
after secretly giving birth Wednesday, and her husband, Louis, saw
and held the baby for the first time.
   The parents decided to name the brown-haired, blue-eyed baby
Alyssa Frances, attorneys said. Nurses at Mills Memorial Hospital
in San Mateo, where the child was listed in good condition Friday,
had named her Elizabeth.
   ``We are going to request in court Monday that the child be
released to him as its father, and there are no charges against
him,'' said Vicki Yeley, attorney for Louis Locasto, at a news
conference following the visit.
   But social workers, citing Mrs. Locasto's actions, said they
would seek to have the baby kept out of the family's custody.
   The child was found crying, swathed in bloody towels, beneath a
sink on the United Airlines DC-10 on Wednesday shortly after the
plane landed at San Francisco International Airport on a flight
from Newark, N.J.
   Investigators believe the newborn had been there for six hours,
since shortly before the plane took off at Newark. Mrs. Locasto,
24, of New York City surrendered early Thursday after authorities
traced her name from the passenger list.
   Mrs. Locasto was charged with felony child endangerment and was
released after posting $50,000 bail late Thursday.
   Her husband, who was with her on the flight, was not charged.
Her family was apparently unaware that she was pregnant, officials
said.
   Although both parents visited with the baby Friday, only the
father attended the news conference. Locasto, the owner of a
limousine service, did not speak, deferring to his lawyer.
   Yeley noted that the family has two other daughters, ages 18
months and 6 years, and said the father is very upset. On Thursday,
Mrs. Locasto's attorney, John L. Williams, described her in similar
terms, saying she was ``very remorseful, very distraught.''
   The child is currently in the custody of the San Mateo County's
Children's Protective Services. A hearing is set for Monday in
juvenile court to determine whether to continue the county's
temporary custody; permanent custody will be decided later.
   In court papers filed with the county Juvenile Court, social
workers asked to retain custody for another 10 days, until a
hearing to examine Mrs. Locasto's actions during the flight.
   Both Locastos plan to attend Monday's closed custody hearing,
according to their attorneys.
   Detectives said Friday that Mrs. Locasto expressed no interest
in the infant after her arrest.
   ``She never has said one thing about the kid. ... She never
asked how it was,'' said Sheriff's Sgt. Bob Morse. But he said she
admitted giving birth to the child and putting her under the sink.
   Flight attendants told investigators that as the jetliner crew
was preparing for takeoff from Newark, a female passenger asked to
use the bathroom. The flight was delayed for a half-hour as flight
attendants knocked on the restroom door, urging the woman to come
out so the trip could begin.
   The woman finally emerged and rejoined her husband and children,
investigators said. Flight attendants found the bathroom splattered
with blood, but sealed it off in the belief the woman had an
extreme case of diarrhea. It remained locked until after the plane
landed.
   The Locastos left the airplane with other passengers, and a
cleaning crew found the infant about 20 minutes later.
</TEXT>
