<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Sihanouk     07-16 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Sihanouk,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk To Visit Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Norodom Sihanouk, who announced on Monday
his resignation as head of the Cambodian resistance coalition, will
visit Japan as scheduled in August, according to news reports
Saturday.
   In a message to Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno, Sihanouk said he
would like to visit Japan as planned despite earlier reports he had
canceled the visit, according to the economic daily Nihon Keizai
Shimbun. It gave no attribution for its report.
   Sihanouk is due to come to Japan Aug. 8 for a four-day visit.
   Conflicting reports arose about Sihanouk's plans after he
resigned as president of the Cambodian guerrilla coalition _ an
alliance of his followers, anti-communists and the radical Khmer
Rouge (Red Cambodians).
   In his resignation he accused the Khmer Rouge of attacking his
supporters.
   Sihlanouk was deposed as head of state in March 1970 and the
monarchy was abolished later that year.
   The Khmer Rouge gained power in the spring of 1975, defeating
the U.S.-backed government, and Cambodians by the hundreds of
thousands were killed under its harsh policies. Vietnam invaded
Camdodia in December 1978, ousted the Khmer Rouge and established
another communist government.
   Foreign Ministry officials contacted by The Associated Press
said that after Sihanouk resigned from the coalition Japan extended
again the invitation for his visit but did not receive a formal
reply.
   Sihanouk is expected to meet Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and
Uno to discuss Cambodian peace talks, the Kyodo News Service
reported.
   Other reports carried in the news media said Sihanouk decided to
go ahead with his visit to Japan in support of Uno's call for free
elections in Cambodia under the surveillance of an international
monitoring group. Uno also has offered to provide Japanese aid to
finance a neutral peacekeeping force in Cambodia.
</TEXT>
