<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Military     07-16 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Military,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joint U.S.-Turkish Venture To Produce Rocket Systems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American group and two Turkish
companies agreed Friday to form a company to produce multiple
launch rocket systems in this NATO-member country.
   The LTV Missiles and Electronic Group of Dallas, Texas, ENKA
Holding of Turkey and the state-owned Turkish Machine and Chemistry
Industry will hold respectively 51 percent, 35 percent and 14
percent of the shares in the company, officials said.
   Financing for the project will be worked out later and will
involve credit from the U.S. side of the venture, a Defense
Ministry spokesman said.
   A total of 180 rocket systems are to be co-produced in Turkey.
The project will cost an estimated $1 billion over 10 years,
Defense Minister Ercan Vuralhan said at the signing ceremony. He
said it will bring technological skills to Turkey and will have
export potential.
   Production of rocket systems is part of a Turkish plan to
modernize the country's armed forces, the largest in NATO after
those of the United States.
   Under the plan Turkey has started co-producing F-16 fighter
jets. Recently a California company, the Food Machinery Corp.,
signed a $1 billion contract to manufacture armored combat vehicles
in Turkey.
</TEXT>
