<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Peronists     07-16 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Peronists,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Returns Give Populist a Peronist Victory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peronists elected a populist who
favors a partial moratorium on foreign debt to face the governing
party candidate in next year's presidential elections, final
returns showed Friday.
   The returns from the first Peronist Party primary in four
decades, held a week ago, gave an upset victory to provincial Gov.
Carlos Menem with 54 percent of the vote.
   His opponent, Peronist Party President Antonio Cafiero, took 46
percent.
   The principal presidential opponent of Menem, the 53-year-old
governor of the mountainous western province of La Rioja, will be
Cordoba provincial Gov. Eduardo Angeloz of the governing Radical
Civic Union Party.
   Angeloz, 57, was the only Radical party governor re-elected in
last September's gubernatorial races. The Peronists, overcoming
nationwide electoral losses in 1983 and 1985, routed the Radicals
to win 17 of the 22 governor's seats.
   Menem was elected the Peronist standard-bearer by 1.6 million
card-carrying Justicialist Party members, more commonly known as
Peronists for founder President Gen. Juan Peron.
   A populist, Menem appeals especially to union members and the
lower class. However, he also beat Cafiero on his home turf,
populous Buenos Aires Province.
   Menem favors a moratorium on the interest portion of Argentina's
$55 billion foreign debt, the third largest in the developing world.
   President Raul Alfonsin, elected in 1983 to end a nearly
eight-year military dictatorship, by law cannot run for re-election.
   His term expires in December 1989. Presidential elections are
tentatively set for May or June of that year.
</TEXT>
