<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0622EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Banks     07-16 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Banks,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panamanian Banks To Ease Withdrawal Restrictions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Limits on withdrawals from bank
checking accounts will be eased in another reduction of
restrictions that were imposed after most banks were closed in
March, the Banking Commission announced Friday.
   It said that beginning Monday customers will be allowed to
withdraw up to 50 percent of the balance that they had in their
checking accounts as of March 3, but with a maximum withdrawal of
$50,000.
   The remaining amount in checking accounts may be transferred to
savings or fixed-term deposits under the new regulations.
   On March 3, the government closed 67 of the country's 117 banks
after a run on deposits brought about by the political crisis
involving Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the head of Panama's Defense
Forces and dominant force in the civilian government. The banks
that were closed were licensed to conduct both local and
international business.
   They were allowed to reopen May 9 and on July 4 the withdrawal
limit from checking accounts was increased from 25 percent to 40
percent of the balance and the maximum from $10,000 to $20,000.
   A $50-dollar-per-month maximum on withdrawals from savings
accounts remains in effect.
   People began scrambling to withdraw their funds from banks on
Feb. 26 after Noriega deposed President Eric Arturo Delvalle, the
day after Delvalle had tried to fire the general. Noriega was
indicted in February by federal grand juries in Florida on charges
of drug trafficking and the U.S. government subsequently imposed
economic sanctions against Panama.
   A U.S. freeze on $50 million of Panamanian government money left
the National Bank of Panama, a commercial and central bank, unable
to cover the large withdrawals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
