<DOCNO> AP880716-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0835EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Dmytryk Adv20   07-16 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Dmytryk, Adv 20,0835</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, July 20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Survivor of Hollywood's Unfriendly 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, SPAIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Filmmaker Edward Dmytryk makes this grim
prediction: ``When I die, I know the obits will read `one of
Hollywood's Unfriendly 10,' not `director of `The Caine Mutiny,'
`The Young Lions,' `Raintree County' and other films.'''
   Still vital at 79 and a teacher of film at the University of
Southern California, Dmytryk was in Spain for a symposium on the
Hollywood Blacklist at the Barcelona Film Festival. He made the
trip from Los Angeles knowing that his appearance at the July 4
panel could cause fireworks. And it did.
   The festival also invited directors Jules Dassin (``Rififi,''
``Never on Sunday'') and John Berry (``Claudine,'' ``Thieves''),
and writer Walter Bernstein (``Little Miss Marker,'' ``The
Front''). All three were refused employment in the Hollywood
studios during the 1950s because of alleged Communist Party
membership.
   Dmytryk and writer Ring Lardner Jr. (``M-A-S-H'') are the two
surviving members of the Unfriendly 10 who declined to testify
about communist membership before a congressional committee and
served prison terms for contempt of Congress. Dmytryk emerged from
six months imprisonment and testified about his party membership,
naming names of fellow members.
   Those events happened 40 years ago, but the antipathies remain.
Dassin, Berry and Bernstein refused to appear on the platform with
Dmytryk. He sat in the audience with his wife, the former actress,
Jean Porter, and heard himself excoriated as ``informer,''
``Judas'' and ``scum'' by his three former comrades.
   ``I didn't give any names that weren't already known by the
FBI,'' Dmytryk responded. He told of entering the Communist Party
``with dreams and ideals; when you finally found out that those
dreams and ideals were all garbage, you hated like hell to lose
them.''
   After 90 minutes of heated exchanges, Dassin announced, ``I do
not wish to be engaged in a symposium with Mr. Dmytryk.'' He left
the room, accompanied by Berry and Bernstein. The audience was
stunned. Mrs. Dmytryk bowed her head and wept.
   In his hotel room, Edward Dmytryk glanced back at those
turbulent days when Hollywood _ and the nation _ was caught up in
the Red hunting fever. He said he had joined the party in 1945
because he thought it was active in some good causes. At that time
he was one of RKO's hottest directors, having made ``Murder, My
Sweet,'' which started a whole genre of private-eye movies.
   The only point of agreement among all four panelists was that no
communist propaganda ever reached the screen; the studio bosses
were too alert to allow that. But some of the hard-core party
members tried.
   ``My disillusionment with the party started after I had finished
and edited `Cornered,''' he recalled. ``Both Adrian Scott (producer
and one of the Unfriendly 10) and I had taken out all of the
communist propaganda that the scriptwriter had put in. The script
was full of manifestos and was impossible to make.
   ``Adrian and I were called on the carpet (by party leaders) and
told to put the propaganda back in. But the picture was already
finished. And if I had shot the original script, the studio would
have put it on the shelf or thrown it out completely.''
   Dmytryk said he remained in the party ``only a few months.'' But
in 1948 he was among the 10 witnesses before the House Committe on
Un-American Activities who cited the First Amendment in refusing to
testify.
   ``That was a mistake; later witnesses cited the Fifth Amendment
and were not tried,'' he said.
   If he had left the party, why didn't he testify?
   ``I didn't want to do it before jail, because they would call me
a coward. They'd say I was doing it simply to stay out of jail,''
he said.
   ``I made my first announcement that I had been a member just
before I got out of jail. That didn't satisfy the other side.''
   In 1951, Dmytryk appeared before the committee to tell of his
disillusionment with the party, and he identified 26 people as
communists.
   ``I didn't feel guilty about talking,'' he said. ``I knew what
would happen: that they would call me a rat. But I did what I
wanted to do. I have never regretted it.''
   The director's recanting did not immediately revive his career.
His first assignment was a quickie for which he was paid $500. Then
Stanley Kramer assigned him to a series of modest-budget films,
followed by `The Caine Mutiny.'' He became one of Hollywood's
busiest directors, making ``Broken Lance'' (Spencer Tracy),
``Soldier of Fortune'' (Clark Gable), ``Raintree County''
(Elizabeth Taylor, Montgomery Clift), ``The Young Lions'' (Clift,
Marlon Brando) and ``The Carpetbaggers'' (George Peppard, Alan
Ladd).
   Dmytryk turned from directing to teaching 10 years ago and has
written textbooks on filmmaking.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Wed July 20</NOTE>
