<DOCNO> AP880716-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0834EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-Drought-TheChases-I Adv18   07-16 1011</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-The Chases-I, Adv 18,1042</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, July 18, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Part I: For Gordon and Jean Chase, So Many `What Ifs?'</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphics</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The drought of '88 is a test of will for farm
families from the Appalachians to the Rockies. With this article,
an AP correspondent begins a series of reports on how the
developing disaster is touching one such family. Other articles
will follow from time to time, tracing the course of the drought
through the eyes of the Chases of Barry County, Michigan.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HASTINGS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Each day, Kurt Chase surveys his family's
parched fields, wondering if that day's intense heat and dry winds
will spell the difference between survival and disaster for the
withering crops.
   ``Sometimes it looks so bad, I don't know if they can stand one
more day of it,'' says Chase, who spends about 60 hours a week
working in the fields with his father, Gordon.
   For the Chase family, the biggest fear is the fear of the
unknown.
   ``There are so many `What ifs,' to ask,'' says Jean Chase,
Gordon's wife, Kurt's mother. ``What if it doesn't rain? What if we
can't pay the bills?''
   Thousands of farmers across the nation's midsection are asking
themselves the same questions. The worst dry spell since the Dust
Bowl of the 1930s presents few certainties.
   The wind gusting across the Chases' dairy and cash-crop farm
sometimes blows away the sandy soil to expose seeds that should
have germinated weeks ago.
   Most years, the Chases produce so much feed there's enough left
over to sell after their 300 head of beef and dairy cattle are fed.
   Not this year. The first cutting of hay was weak and the second
almost non-existent.
   ``With the price of soybean meal going up the way it has been,
we're not going to be able to buy any to feed the cows for
protein,'' Gordon Chase says softly, nervously rubbing his
forehead. ``The impact of what we might be in for really didn't hit
me until just recently.''
   As they sit in their living room, in matching blue recliners,
the blond-haired couple look younger than their 51 years.
   Outside, in the arid air, an American flag hangs limply from a
pole. Inside, in the non-air-conditioned house, big fans, turned up
full blast, ease the 90-degree-plus heat.
   Gordon and Jean met in high school. They married 32 years ago.
Now they sit surrounded by framed photographs of three children and
six grandchildren, by a rambling, white, two-story farmhouse, and
by their 1,100 acres _ 400 their own, 700 rented _ in the rolling
countryside of southwest Michigan's Barry County.
   Mrs. Chase does the bookkeeping and helps work the fields. But
morale-boosting is her main job, she says. ``If you don't keep
yourself up, nothing else matters.''
   Last year was one of the family's most profitable, as it was for
many farmers, and at the start of this season their projected
income was the highest it had ever been.
   But the cloudless skies have turned much of their hay, wheat and
soybean fields into barren lots of dust.
   They have given up on most of their 350 acres of corn, deciding
to use their limited irrigation to keep 60 acres alive. The rest
will be used to feed their cattle.
   Since April 1, Barry County has received less than six inches of
rain _ barely half the normal rainfall. It has gotten drier as time
goes on. The forecasters say the steady rain needed to reverse the
impending disaster is unlikely through at least July. By then it
may be too late.
   ``We're at a critical point,'' Gordon Chase says, sinking back
into his chair. ``I don't know what we're going to do if it doesn't
rain. I guess just hope that your lenders will be a little
lenient.''
   For the Chases, this is the most trying period since they fell
victim to the sky-high interest rates of the late 1970s and early
'80s and almost lost more than half their farm.
   Six years ago they hired a financial consultant and
``restructured.'' About four years ago, Kurt, 28, and his wife,
Dena, 27, entered into partnership with the Chases. The family has
since seem some good seasons.
   But this year they are more than ever preoccupied with weather
reports and crop prices. They watch the ups and downs of Chicago
Board of Trade prices on a computer screen in their home office.
   ``We might be better off than most, but we are very, very
financially stressed,'' Mrs. Chase says. They may end up struggling
to cover feed, seed and other operating expenses that could
approach $100,000 this year.
   No amount of planning can immunize them from a drought. They
recently applied for $7,300 worth of drought insurance for 500
acres, but have been told that they will probably be turned down
because of excessive demand.
   The Chases often attend professional farm-management seminars.
   ``We have high school educations, but we learn to tap into every
resource we can,'' she says. ``I think that's what's gotten us
through some very hard times.''
   Gordon and Kurt are working overtime to produce extra milk from
their 125 milking cows, to make up for projected crop shortfalls.
   ``Farmers have got to be one of the most optimistic kinds of
people _ things are always going to be better next year,'' says
Gordon Chase. ``We're fighters and will fight as long as we can _
up to the point of reality. ...
   ``It really gets to us when we hear people talking about how
brown their lawns are getting. This is our life here.''
   Mrs. Chase thinks of the drought as a test _ not only of the
family's farming abilities but also of their faith. Their church
services include special prayers for rain.
   ``Maybe this is making us all aware of our priorities,'' she
says. ``We take so much for granted.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs, July 18, or Thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
