<DOCNO> AP880716-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0835EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-Drought-TheChases-II Adv25   07-16 1097</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-The Chases-II, Adv 25,1125</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release monday PMs, July 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Part II: Coping with Drought, Chases Haunted by Earlier Crisis</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphics</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The drought searing the midlands is the second
crisis of the decade for many American farmers. This report, part
of a periodic series on the impact of the drought on one family,
the Chases of Barry County, Michigan, looks at the economics of
surviving one trial and preparing for another.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HASTINGS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's not an easy story for Jean and
Gordon Chase to tell. A story of perceived failure never is.
   For the Chases and for countless farmers like them across the
country, the stories of lost land and lost dreams are memories that
should be put to rest. But each passing day of drought _ of intense
heat, high winds, no rain _ brings those painful memories closer to
the surface.
   ``We always felt we were successful. That's why it was so hard
on us and so hard even now to talk about it,'' Mrs. Chase says of
the crisis three years ago in which they nearly lost most of their
dairy and cash-crop farm here in southwest Michigan.
   The crisis was 10 years in the making, beginning when the Chases
tried to borrow money in 1975 to buy a 237-acre farm to add to the
160 acres they bought from Mrs. Chases' parents 10 years earlier.
   Because her parents had farmed only part time, the Chases
consider themselves first-generation farmers. ``When we started, we
didn't have $25 in our pockets,'' Mrs. Chase says. ``Gord just had
the desire.''
   ``Gord'' and Jean, bringing up three children, had a successful
few years in the business and found it easy to borrow money in the
inflationary 1970s.
   ``Everything was put at such an inflated value, all your
equipment and land, that the banks couldn't give you enough to
borrow because of all your collateral,'' says Chase, relighting his
pipe and recalling the mistake that almost cost the former truck
driver his dream of being a farmer.
   But then inflation eased, crop prices fell and banks quit
lending in 1982. The Chases, like so many farmers, were still
saddled with high-interest debt, but their income was declining.
Many farmers faced bankruptcy. Many kept trying to borrow just to
survive.
   ``It just kept snowballing, and suddenly, we were trapped,''
Mrs. Chase says. In 10 years they spent about $300,000 in interest
on about $20,000 in principal on that one farm.
   ``There's a saying,'' Chase says. ``If you can't keep up, you
can't catch up.''
   When the Chases tried to find private investors in 1982 to help
them out of their hole, they wound up finding a financial
consultant instead. ``He told us `You don't need more money, you
need to manage it better,''' Mrs. Chase says.
   Acting on his advice, the cost of which rose from $250 to $500
per monthly session, the Chases sold 40 percent of their dairy
herd, keeping the healthiest and most profitable. He also urged
them to enter a partnership with their son and daughter-in-law,
trading some of their high-interest debt for lower interest rates
offered the young couple.
   But the land was still worth less than the debt they carried on
it. In 1985, unable to meet the repayment schedule, the Chases were
advised by their consultant to give up the farm, deeding it to Farm
Land Bank.
   Then, under the new arrangement, they leased it back _ parcel by
parcel _ with an option to repurchase. They never stopped farming.
They came up with the monthly rent, were finally able to borrow at
lower interest rates, and then bought it back.
   ``It was probably the worst year of our lives. Many tears were
shed,'' Mrs. Chase says. ``But if we hadn't done it, we probably
wouldn't be farming today.''
   The worst part of their agonizing decision to give up the farm
was that their friends and neighbors could see their ``failure.''
Though hoping to keep the transaction private, the Chases found
their land on the growing list of farms for sale published by
Federal Land Bank, now Farm Credit Services.
   ``This is a community where everybody knows everybody, and all
of a sudden it became coffee shop news that our farm was for
sale,'' Mrs. Chase says with tear-filled eyes, recalling the
family's sense of humiliation.
   As soon as the news got out, ``we felt surrounded by vultures,''
Chase says. ``Seven or eight neighbors would have done anything to
get that land.''
   They say one neighbor on the Farmers Home Administration's local
board urged the other two members to deny the Chases' application
for a low-interest loan. But the Chases won an appeal at the state
level.
   ``There's a sense of pride when you own land that I can't
compare to anything else,'' Mrs. Chase says. ``To see that farm in
the newspaper hurt more than I can explain.''
   The Chases completed their repurchase of the farm last January.
Before the drought hit, they expected this to be their best year,
and they hoped to be debt-free in five years. But now
``everything's looking different,'' says Chase.
   The Chases just hope to cover their $50,000 annual expenses for
seed, fertilizer, chemicals and fuel for irrigation. The feed they
must buy for their 300 head of cattle usually costs $35,000 for the
year, but the price of the soybean meal continues to climb. With
careful planning, the Chases hope to have enough feed to get them
through the fall.
   They pre-sold 30 percent of their soybean crop at $7 a bushel at
the start of the season. But what was then considered 30 percent
may now make up their total soybean harvest. And now soybeans are
going for $10 a bushel. Only 60 acres of their 350-acre cornfield
looks salvageable.
   The Chases feel fortunate their dairy operation accounts for 60
percent of their income. But they worry that the federal government
might go through with a cut in milk price supports next January, as
planned.
   Working 60-hour weeks in the fields, taking on the heavy job of
moving their irrigation system to spots where it can do the most
good, the Chases sometimes wonder why they bother.
   Gordon Chase, a fan of motivational tapes, says he's trying to
take the experts' advice, view the drought as a temporary setback,
and keep going.
   ``It's easy to say it,'' he says, ``but close up this is the
real thing.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, July 25</NOTE>
