<1ST_LINE>a i AM-MountainDesert Adv21   07-16 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mountain Desert, Adv 21,0747</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, July 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Himalayan Desert Region Springs to Life in Summer</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEEMA SIROHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Isolated and dreary all winter long, Leh
springs to life in summer when vegetables ripen in the fields and
tourists swarm in from 11,500 feet below, filling up 80 hotels and
guest houses in the world's highest desert.
   Women wearing shining strings of turquoise and coral greet the
visitors with shy smiles and a soft ``julley'' _ hello.
   With about 10,000 permanent residents, Leh is the major town of
India's Ladakh region, a Himalayan desert because high surrounding
mountains block rain and snow. But the area is cut off when snow at
lower altitudes block roads and the region's 68,000 people settle
in for eight months of winter privation.
   But this time of year people and supplies flow in and Leh, known
as the ``Last Shangri-La,'' vibrates.
   Stark, brown mountains surround the town and the Buddhist
monasteries perched on hilltops.
   The moonlike landscape is broken occasionally by splashes of
willow and poplar and small farms growing wheat, barley and
vegetables.
   Come June, the Leh valley fills with Europeans and Americans _
tourists and mountain trekkers.
   The road from Srinagar, the capital of Kashmir, opens as the
snow melts down the mountains.
   ``Last year, even matchsticks were not available because the
road closed early and opened late,'' said Akbar Ladakhi, a
long-time resident.
   ``People survive on tsempa,'' he said.
   Tsempa, a salted paste of chickpea flour, is eaten sometimes
with onions and sometimes thinned into a soup. Wealthier Ladakhis
spice their winters with a barley wine.
   But with summer, these high-desert people feast on tomatoes,
turnips, carrots, peas, potatoes and beans, all either grown
locally or shipped from below when the road opens.
   Akbar Ladakhi said tourism has helped improve the region's
economy, providing money for reviving dying arts, restoring
monastries and preserving old Buddhist paintings.
   But some others feel tourists have commercialized Ladakh, where
merchants once slept amid their wares and buyers simply took goods
and left money behind.
   ``Corruption culture has invaded us. People have become clever
and business-minded,'' said Sonam Wangchuk, a student involved in
promoting Ladakhi culture and dance.
   He complained youngsters were becoming Westernized, discarding
their traditional robes for T-shirts and jeans. Leh's main street
is filled with the music of Hindi movies and and Michael Jackson.
   For the summer tourists, restaurants offer an array of Chinese
and Tibetan foods but cooks also have mastered apple and banana
pancakes for those preferring a Western-style breakfast.
   Ladakh is a predominantly Buddhist region influenced over the
centuries by nearby Tibet. The region was originally a Tibetan
province and is still known as ``Little Tibet.''
   But rock carvings found nearby indicate Ladakh had been used for
thousands of years by nomadic tribes, including the Mons of north
India, the Dards of Baltistan and the Mongols of central Asia.
   Ladakh's Golden Age began in 1533 when King Soyang Namgyal
united the region, established his capital at Leh, and extended his
boundaries to the outskirts of Lhasa in Tibet.
   Kashmiri rulers invaded in the last century and, since India's
independence from Britain in 1947, the region has been caught up in
India's border wars with Pakistan and China.
   The Namgyal Palace overlooking Leh stands as a mute testimony to
the battles, its sprawling walls bearing wide, gaping holes.
   Most Ladakhis are followers of the Dalai Lama, the exiled
god-king of Tibet who lives in the Indian Himalayan town of
Dharamsala.
   Tibetan prayer flags flutter over most houses and shops, their
colors fading under summer's bright sun.
   Being near the Indian-Chinese border, Ladakh also is an army
base. Convoys of army trucks spew black smoke along the narrow
roads. The army also is the region's biggest employer, hiring local
people to build military roads and dams.
   But most work ends in September when winter begins. People lay
in food and firewood; only emergency goods are brought in by army
planes.
   Temperatures go down to 18 degrees below zero Farhenheit and
prices soar.
   But Wangchuk, the traditionalist, says the people are enured to
it.
   ``We have grown up with hardship,'' he said. ``It doesn't matter
if you don't have vegetables or milk.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, July 21</NOTE>
