<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions July 16-17</NOTE>
<HEAD>Greenspan Keeps Them Guessing on Wall Street</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alan Greenspan has made his intentions clear to
Wall Street: The Federal Reserve either will, or will not, tighten
credit further in the weeks ahead.
   Making his midsummer appearance before a congressional committee
on Wednesday, the Fed chairman expressed a goodly measure of
concern about the prospect of increased inflation if economic
growth begins to strain the capacity of production facilities and
the labor force.
   As a result, he said, the central bank ``might be well advised
to err more on the side of restrictiveness rather than of
stimulus.''
   At the same time, however, he said higher interest rates were
not inevitable, and indicated he was in no rush to raise the
discount rate _ the rate the Fed charges on loans to private
financial institutions, and one of its most visible tools for
influencing trends in money and credit.
   The next morning, a headline in one major newspaper declared
``Greenspan Signals Higher Interest Rates,'' while another
reported, ``Greenspan Sees Stable Rates.''
   All in a day's work for Wall Street's Fed watchers. The job
description for the top job at the Fed stresses the ability to talk
before Congress for long periods of time without saying much of
anything.
   Some find this sort of thing offensive, arguing that an
organization with as much power as the Fed should be more
accountable to the citizenry and their elected representatives in a
democracy.
   But defenders of the present way of doing things say that
whoever speaks for the Fed is obliged to choose his words
carefully, if only because of the financial markets' tendency
toward emotional overreaction.
   In order to pursue its policies effectively, they say, the Fed
must keep a close eye on how the bond market, in particular, is
behaving.
   Suppose, for example, that the Fed sought to ease credit and
lower interest rates in circumstances that bond traders saw as
potentially inflationary. They would then tend to push interest
rates up, not down.
   The stock market behaved through the past week as if it had
learned nothing startlingly new about the Fed's intentions. Prices
meandered in a narrow range, and the Dow Jones average of 30
industrials closed Friday at 2,129.45, up 23.30 points from the
week before.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index rose .84 to 153.65;
the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market gained
.26 to 394.59; and the American Stock Exchange market value index
increased .29 at 309.31.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 175.20 million shares a day,
against 163.40 in the previous week.
   As circumspect as he was about the future, Greenspan did confirm
that the Fed took a series of steps during the spring toward
tighter credit when it became increasingly clear that the economy
was stronger than expected.
   ``Skepticism about the Fed's resolve to resist inflationary
pressures persists,'' observed David Resler, economist at Nomura
Securities International, in a midyear appraisal of the outlook.
   ``Many suspect that the Fed will be too slow to take necessary
action against inflation during the election year.''
   However, Resler said, ``the three credit tightening moves that
the Fed took over an eight-week span in the second quarter ought to
assuage fears that the Fed will not respond quickly and decisively
to inflation pressures whenever they surface.
   ``Moreover, the financial markets' hypersensitivity to signs of
inflation renders fruitless any attempt to steer the economy along
an unwarranted growth path.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions July 16-17</NOTE>
