<NOTE>For Release Monday July 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>Job Growth: Too Much of a Good Thing?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the stock and bond markets have made clear
lately, Wall Street investors have very mixed feelings about the
strong employment growth that has occurred this year.
   Providing jobs, of course, is one of the basic goals of economic
policymakers.
   So when the unemployment rate falls to a 14-year low, as it did
in June, something obviously is going right.
   The question facing investors, however, is whether and when
gains in employment become too much of a good thing _ reaching a
point where the capacity of the labor force is strained, unleashing
new inflationary forces.
   On that point, the views of Wall Street economists diverge
widely. Some say the danger point is close at hand, while others
argue that circumstances allow for plenty more growth.
   The optimists point out that while nonfarm payroll employment
grew by 346,000 in June, the Labor Department's measure of hourly
wages actually declined.
   Nevertheless, argues Allen Sinai, economist at the Boston Co.
and Economic Advisers Inc., ``this is still no great comfort on
inflation worries, since economic and labor market strength
typically comes first and then inflationary pressures second, with
some lag.
   ``With so much strength in labor markets and such low
unemployment rates, it is hard to think that wage inflation will
not keep accelerating.''
   David Levine, economist at Sanford C. Bernstein & Co., points
out that payments to employees make up about two-thirds of the
costs businesses incur in this country.
   ``Unemployment has clearly entered the realm that was associated
with wage and price problems in the early and late 1970s,'' he
maintains.
   ``While wage growth remains quite temperate by the standards of
those years, it has now begun to accelerate.
   ``Assuming, as we do, that above consensus growth (in the gross
national product) will continue to pull down the unemployment rate,
the labor market seems likely to become tighter than at any time
since 1973 and wage pressures should intensify.''
   Levine says he is looking for wage increases in the 6 to 7
percent range next year.
   By contrast, Edward Yardeni, economist at Prudential-Bache
Securities, contends that times have changed in ways that allow for
further job growth without a big increase in inflation.
   In the 1970s and the early 1980s, he says, the baby-boom
generation born after World War II moved into the labor force in
huge numbers. The unemployment rate and inflation both rose.
   Now, because of the ``birth dearth'' in the 1960s, he says
demographic forces are working in the opposite direction.
   Yardeni predicts that the unemployment rate, now at 5.3 percent,
will get as low as 4 percent by 1990, or maybe sooner.
   ``If the unemployment rate is heading toward 4 percent, doesn't
that suggest much higher wage inflation ahead? Not necessarily,''
he says.
   ``We've argued that labor-saving, productivity-enhancing capital
spending is the only intelligent way that corporate America can
respond to the labor shortage.
   ``Of course, they could start a bidding war. But that way
they'll get costlier workers, not more workers. In our opinion,
corporate managers are unlikely to suddenly offer big wage hikes
after they spent five years cutting costs.
   ``The corporate culture of the 1980s (and 1990s) emphasizes cost
cutting. Price increases were fashionable in the 1970s. Global and
domestic pressures suggest that a return to the inflationary
culture of the 1970s is unlikely.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday July 18</NOTE>
