<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-OPEC,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico Criticizes OPEC Oil Production Overruns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto without first name is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Friday criticized
production overruns by some OPEC members that have allowed crude
oil prices to drop on the world market in recent weeks.
   Mexico's view was contained in a message which Energy and Mines
Secretary Fernando Hiriart sent the newly named general secretary
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, Subroto of
Indonesia.
   He said in the message that the international cartel's failure
to adhere to its own, agreed upon export quotas is undermining the
market.
   ``This has prevented crude prices from reaching the expected
levels because of over-production in export platforms,'' the
message released here said.
   Mexico, the world's sixth largest oil exporter, is not a member
of the 13-nation cartel, but it has often cooperated with OPEC by
restricting sales abroad and following its pricing guidelines.
   ``Mexico has actively supported OPEC's measures to stabilize the
international petroleum market and these unilateral decisions were
taken within a context where cooperation and discipline were to be
expected by all members of the cartel's exporters of
hydrocarbons,'' the message said.
   Subroto is expected to arrive in Mexico City on Aug. 17 to
discuss with officials here measures to stabilize the market and
boost prices. Crude oil is this country's principal source of
export earnings.
   Mexico produces an average of 2.5 million barrels of crude a
day, and exports 1.36 million barrels _ about half of it to the
United States. It used to export 1.5 million barrels daily two
years ago, but reduced the amount in order to help keep prices up.
</TEXT>
