<DOCNO> AP880716-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-16-88 0804EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     07-16 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mixed in Light Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude and heating oil prices rose but gasoline
prices declined in light pre-weekend trading that brokers
attributed largely to internal market influences.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August-delivery price
for West Texas Intermediate advanced 10 cents a barrel on Friday to
$14.86.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale No. 2
heating oil rose 0.21 cent a gallon to 41.12 cents, and unleaded
gasoline fell 0.81 cent a gallon to 49.73 cents.
   Brokers said crude and heating oil prices rose partly from
short-covering, the purchase of contracts by speculators to replace
borrowed contracts they had sold earlier. Short-covering can cause
short-term price rises.
   Others attributed the advances partly to a tendency by many
traders to reduce risky positions heading into a weekend. ``We've
got a lot of people squaring up their books,'' said Peter Beutel,
assistant director at Elders Futures Inc., a New York
energy-futures trading concern.
   Traders said the decline in gasoline came from pre-weekend
profit taking. Contrary to recent declines in oil prices, gasoline
has been rising sharply because of unprecedented demand and tight
supplies in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
